1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be2 Bb4 8. O-O
O-O {I think this is best here.} (8... Bxc3 $5 9. bxc3 d6 {has been tried a
few times and it looks like a valid alternative, for example:} 10. f3 O-O 11.
Ba3 Rd8 12. Qd2 (12. Nb3 Nc6 $11) 12... Nbd7 13. Rfd1 (13. Nb3 Ne5 14. Rfd1
Nxc4 15. Bxc4 Qxc4 16. Bxd6 Ne8 {should be close to equality.}) 13... Ne5 14.
c5 d5 15. c4 (15. exd5 $1 exd5 16. Rab1 Bd7 $11) 15... Bd7 16. cxd5 exd5 17.
exd5 Nxd5 18. Rac1 Re8 {Black has equalized although he still needs to be
careful because white's bishop pair should not be underestimated. A plan is
Rad8, h6, and perhaps Nc6. Here GM Morovic played} 19. Nf5 $6 Bxf5 20. Qxd5
Rad8 {black has an easy game. Morovic Fernandez, I (2572)-Pichot, A (2532) San
Salvador ESA 2016}) 9. Bg5 (9. Qd3 {is an important alternative that I analyze
separately in Anand, V (2779)-Ivanchuk, V (2747) Doha QAT 2016}) (9. f3 {
could transpose to the 8.f3 line. Here black can answer in more than just one
way for example:} d5 $5 {could be a good try for equality} (9... b6 {keeps
things in tension and we analyze this setup in A2 8.f3 line}) (9... Nc6 $5 10.
Be3 (10. Nxc6 {here black can recapture with either pawn, 10...dxc6 looks solid
} dxc6 11. Be3 Bd6 (11... b5 $5) 12. f4 e5 13. f5 (13. c5 Be7 $15) 13... b5 {
and black should be able to create enough counterplay following Qe7-Rd8-Bb7}
14. g4 {the only dangerous try.} h6 15. h4 Qe7 16. Qe1 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 18.
Kh2 Nh7 19. Qg3 Qe7 20. Rad1 Bb7 {followed by Rad8 and is white who needs to
be careful already}) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bd4
dxe4 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. fxe4 Qe5 $132 {After this forced sequence black has
emerged with a worse pawn structure and a somewhat weak king, however, there
is not a lot of material on the board, and black's activity is enough to keep
the balance. In fact, black went on to win in the game Kravtsiv, M (2572)
-Mueller, F (2324) Dresden 2014}) 10. cxd5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 exd5 12. Bg5 Nbd7 {
and now} 13. e5 (13. Nf5 dxe4 14. Qd4 Qe5 $1 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11) 13... Qxe5 14.
Qd2 {offers white a dangerous compensation for the pawn, but black should be
able to keep the balance} Nc5 15. Bf4 (15. Rae1 Qd6 $11) 15... Qe7 16. Rae1 Qd8
17. Bd1 Ne6 18. Be5 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Bd7 {followed by Re8}) 9... Bxc3 $1 10. Bxf6
Bxb2 {Black also equalized with 10...Bb4 which seems playable too} (10... Bb4
11. Bg5 Bd6 12. h3 Nc6 {I see no big problems for black at all} 13. Nxc6 dxc6
14. Be3 c5 15. f4 b6 16. e5 Be7 17. Bf3 Bb7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 19. Qc2 Rad8 20. Rad1
Qc6 $11 {Tari,A (2520)-Grandelius,N (2623) Oslo NOR 2015}) 11. Nxe6 {Pretty
but not very effective} dxe6 12. Bxb2 Nc6 {black has a very comfortable
position. The plan is e5 followed by Be6 and then rooks to the D file.} 13. c5
Rd8 14. Qc2 e5 (14... Nd4 15. Bxd4 Rxd4 16. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Bd7 {followed
by Rc8 or Bc6 I prefer black's position}) 15. Bc4 Nd4 (15... Be6 {was also
good here} 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Qc4 Qd7 18. a4 Rac8 {with Nd4 coming}) 16. Bxd4
exd4 17. Rab1 Bd7 18. Bd5 (18. Bd3 {was probably better to keep the bishops})
18... Bc6 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 {Although the position is equal white needs to be
careful here, the d4 pawn is a dangerous passed pawn, and c5 is a weakness.}
20. Rb6 Qc7 21. Qb3 (21. Rd1 {with the idea of Qb2 attacking simultaneously on
b7 and d4 seems like a better idea.} Rac8 22. Qb3 Rd7 23. g3 h5 24. Qb4 Qxc5
25. Rxb7 Qxb4 26. Rxb4 Rc2 $11) 21... Rd7 22. Rd1 Rad8 $15 23. g3 d3 24. Rd6 $6
(24. Qc3 d2 25. Rb2 $11) 24... Rxd6 25. cxd6 Qxd6 26. Qxb7 h5 (26... d2) 27. h4
Qe6 28. Rd2 Qc4 29. Qe7 Rd4 (29... Rb8 30. Kg2 Qd4 $17) 30. Kg2 Qc6 31. Kh2 Qc3
(31... Qxe4 32. Qxe4 Rxe4 33. Rxd3 Re2 34. Ra3 Rxf2+ 35. Kh3 Rf6 {should be a
draw with best play}) 32. Qe8+ Kh7 {Not sure what happened in the actual game.
Here white can make a draw by capturing on f7 0-1 (32) Hamdouchi, H (2616)
-Akopian, V (2657) Doha QAT 2014 [Castellanos, R]} *

