1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be2 Bb4 8. f3
{This should not be too problematic for black at all} O-O 9. O-O b6 {As
explained in the notes of the game Hamdouchi-Akopian black has other
interesting tries in this position. However, the move 9...b6 aims for the
typical setup which leads to a complex game.} 10. Nc2 (10. Bg5 Be7 {the threat
of Ng4} 11. Qd2 Bb7 12. Rac1 d6 13. Rfd1 Nbd7 {leads to a standard hedgehog
position}) 10... Be7 11. Be3 d6 12. Qd2 Bb7 13. Rfd1 Nbd7 14. Rac1 Rac8 15. Bf2
Rfe8 {This is the classical setup for black in this opening. One of the main
ideas for black is to achieve d6-d5 or b6-b5 at some point, although white
will try everything to interfere with this plan.} 16. Ne3 Bf8 (16... Qb8 {
could be another move here. Some ideas with Bd8-Bc7 can be tried sometimes})
17. b3 Qb8 18. Bg3 Ne5 19. Kh1 Nh5 20. Bf2 Nd7 {We have a typical hedgehog
battle which is always tense and favors the stronger player. White tries to
put pressure on black's queenside while black will seek counterplay by means
of d6-d5 break.} (20... Nf6 $142) 21. Ng4 $1 h6 22. Bd4 Be7 23. Bf1 Bc6 24. a4
Nhf6 ({I would be very tempted to play a5. Although black leaves a huge weak
square on b5 he also obtains c5 for the knight and stops the queenside
avalanche.} 24... a5 $5 25. Nb5 Bg5 26. Be3 Bxe3 27. Nxe3 Bxb5 28. axb5 Nhf6
29. Qxd6 Nc5 {with compensation}) 25. Nxf6+ {Although the general rule says
that the side with less space should trade pieces, in the hedgehog is not
clear at all that this is in black's benefit. The main reason is that black
loses potential for counterplay with fewer pieces on the board.} Nxf6 26. b4
$14 Nd7 27. Rb1 Qc7 28. a5 bxa5 29. b5 {Typical method of attack for white} Bb7
(29... axb5 30. cxb5 Bb7 31. b6 $16) 30. b6 Qc6 31. Qa2 Ne5 $2 (31... Nc5 32.
Qxa5 Bg5 $14 {black is passive but white still has to breakthrough which is
not that easy}) 32. c5 $1 Ng6 33. Nb5 $1 $18 {the winning blow} dxc5 34. Na7
cxd4 35. Nxc6 Rxc6 36. Qxa5 Rd8 37. Bxa6 Rc5 38. Rb5 Rc2 39. Bxb7 Nh4 40. e5
Rxg2 41. Be4 {1-0 (41) Shankland,S (2642)-Petrosyan,M (2407) Al-Ain UAE 2014} *

