1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be2 Bb4 8. Nc2
$5 {This is becoming popular lately. It was played by Fischer against Portisch
back in 1962!} Be7 $5 {Black should be satisfied with having ''forced'' white
to retreat his knight to c2. The alternative is to take on c3, but it leads to
positions in which white has a strong initiative on the dark squares.} (8...
Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nc6 (9... Nxe4 10. Qd4 Nf6 11. Bf4 Qd8 12. Bd6 Nc6 13. Qd3 {
black has difficulties here}) (9... O-O 10. Ba3 Nxe4 11. Bxf8 Kxf8 12. Qd3 {
Visanescu, D (2036)-Sandu, M (2261) Calimanesti-Caciulata ROU 2017 Black does
not have enough compensation for the exchange}) 10. f3 (10. Ba3 Nxe4 11. Qd3
Qe5 12. O-O {is also dangerous for black} Nc5 13. Qe3) 10... O-O 11. Ba3 Rd8
12. Bd6 (12. Qd6 $5 $16) 12... Qa5 {with unclear play. Fischer, R-Portisch,L
Varna 1962}) 9. Qd3 {This is the only independent idea for white and the one
that is causing black some headache.} (9. O-O d6 {leads to standard positions}
10. Be3 b6 11. f3 Nbd7 12. Qe1 Bb7 13. Qf2 O-O {and here white should probably
continue with Rfd1, Rac1, Nd4, etc. with a typical play of the hedgehog.
Instead, he was tempted for a kingside expansion that was brilliantly refuted
by Portisch} 14. g4 g6 15. Bh6 $2 (15. Rad1 Rfe8 $13) 15... d5 $3 16. Bxf8 Rxf8
{it turns out that black is already better. White can't cope with the threat
of Bc5 and the capture on e4.} 17. Qg2 dxc4 (17... dxe4 18. fxe4 Nc5 {was also
quite strong}) 18. f4 h6 19. h4 b5 $19 20. g5 hxg5 21. hxg5 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 b4 23.
gxf6 bxc3 24. Bf3 Qxf4 25. bxc3 Nxf6 26. e5 Ne4 27. Qh2 Nf2+ {0-1 (27) Almasi,
I (2375)-Portisch, L (2585) Hungary 1995 A brilliant game by Lajos Portisch.
One of the great champions of the Sicilian Kan}) ({White can also start with} 
9. f4 d6 10. O-O O-O (10... b6) 11. Qd3 Nbd7 12. b4 b6 13. Bb2 Bb7 14. a3 Rac8
15. Rac1 Qb8 16. Qg3 Rfe8 17. Bd3 Bf8 {It is important to understand the
nature of these positions. Objectively, white is better. He controls more
squares, his pieces have an excellent coordination, but black's chances should
not be underestimated. I believe black's position is playable.} 18. Qh3 (18.
Rce1 g6 19. e5 Nh5 20. Qf2 Bh6 21. g3 f5 $1 $132) 18... g6 $5 $146 {Looks
natural in order to give the black king some strenght} (18... Red8 $2 {Fier,A 
(2568) -Mohammad, N (2408) Sharjah UAE 2017 White could have taken over the
initiative with} 19. g4 $1 $16) 19. f5 {Looks critical} (19. Ne3 Bg7 {Black
looks solid to me.}) 19... exf5 20. exf5 {black can defend in two ways} g5 {
looks like a drastic solution} (20... Bg7 {is the alternative, and it seems
that black holds} 21. fxg6 (21. Ne3 Re7 $1 $132 {followed by Rce8}) 21... fxg6
$5 {The other recapture is also possible but with this black takes some
pressure off f7. Ne5 is coming or Re7 followed by Rce8}) 21. Qg3 h6 22. h4 d5
$1 {this break comes just in time to ease the pressure} 23. Qxb8 Rxb8 24. Nxd5
Bxd5 25. cxd5 b5 {black has enough counterplay.}) 9... b6 (9... O-O 10. Qg3 d6
11. O-O Nbd7 {could be a move order to avoid 11.Bf4 which is a bit unpleasant
for black.}) 10. Qg3 (10. O-O Bb7) 10... d6 (10... Qxg3 11. hxg3 $16 {this
cannot be recommended.}) 11. f4 {White has another move here that we should
take seriously} (11. Bf4 $5 {played in Popov,I (2613)-Papin,V (2569) Olginka
2011 is even more dangerous} Nbd7 (11... Nc6 12. Rd1) 12. Rd1 (12. Qxg7 Rg8 13.
Qh6 Bb7 14. O-O Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Ne3 Qc5 {with a very unclear position.})
12... Ne5 13. Qxg7 Rg8 14. Qh6 Bb7 (14... Neg4 15. Bxg4 Rxg4 16. Bg3 Nxe4 17.
Ne3 Rg6 18. Qxh7 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Bb7 20. Ne2 $16) 15. Ne3 O-O-O $5 16. O-O (16.
f3 Kb8 17. Bg3 Rg6 18. Qh3 h5 $44) 16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 $13 18. Bg3 Bg5 19.
Qh3 f5 20. Rd4 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Qc6 22. Rfd1 Nf7 $132) 11... Bb7 (11... O-O {
could save a lot of trouble for black and likely transpose to positions
similar to what we have analyzed above.} 12. f5 Kh8 $132) 12. e5 (12. f5 {
is an interesting idea here} e5 (12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Qxg7 $16) 13. Nb4
Nbd7 14. Nbd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Nf6 16. O-O $16 {white should be better in this
position.}) 12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Nfd7 14. O-O Qxe5 (14... Nc6 $1 {As often in
chess, development is the answer!} 15. Nd5 (15. Qxg7 O-O-O {gives black a very
dangerous attack, decisive I would say} 16. Qxf7 Rhg8 $36) (15. Bf4 g5 $1 ({or
} 15... O-O-O $17) 16. Bxg5 O-O-O $132) 15... exd5 16. e6 Qxg3 17. exd7+ Kxd7
18. hxg3 Ne5 $1 {black is not worse at all, if anything he should be better
after he finish coordinating his pieces.}) 15. Bf4 Qc5+ 16. Kh1 g5 17. Bc7 {
White is threatening 18.b4! winning the queen 18...Qc6 19.Nd4+-} e5 $2 {
Black panics} (17... h5 $3 {would have kept things unclear} 18. Na4 (18. b4 $2
h4 $19) 18... Qc6 19. Bf3 h4 $8 20. Bxc6 hxg3 21. Bxb7 Ra7 {black regains his
piece and maintains the balance.} 22. Bxg3 (22. Bxb8 $2 {fails after} Rxh2+ 23.
Kg1 Nxb8 24. Bf3 b5 $19) 22... Rxb7 {I prefer black's position}) 18. Bxb8 $18
Rxb8 19. Ne3 {The white knights arrive on f5 and d5 with a devastating effect
on the black king} Nf6 20. Nf5 Rg8 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. cxd5 Qxd5 23. Rad1 Qa5 24.
Nxe7 Kxe7 25. b4 Bxg2+ 26. Kxg2 {1-0 (26) Sutovsky,E (2646)-Gorovets,A (2524)
Minsk BLR 2017 The Week in Chess 1178 [Castellanos, R]} *

