1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Qc7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Be2 Bb4 8. Qd3
{This move doesn't have any particular independence to our repertoire and will
likely transpose to the lines examined already. I have decided to include this
game because it's worth seeing anyway.} b6 (8... O-O 9. Nc2 (9. O-O Nc6 {
takes us to Anand-Ivanchuk Doha 2016}) (9. Bg5 {is strongly met with} Qe5 $1
10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nc2 Bc5 13. Rad1 d6 {and black is comfortable.
Bergez,L (2371)-Markowski,T (2570) Geneve 2005}) 9... Be7 10. O-O d6 {with
similar ideas to the lines examined in Sutovsky-Gorovets Minsk 2017}) 9. Nc2
Be7 10. O-O (10. Qg3 d6) 10... Bb7 11. Be3 {White opts for a classical maroczy
setup. This is a positional way of playing.} d6 12. Rac1 Nbd7 13. f3 Rc8 14.
Qd2 O-O 15. Rfd1 Qb8 16. Kh1 Rfe8 {Both sides make their standard moves
improving the position and placing each piece in ideal squares.} 17. Bf4 {
Let's see some options here:} (17. Nd4 {this move with the idea of 18.b4 and
19.Nb3 is one of white's main ideas in this setup Here we can continue with}
Ne5 $1 18. Na4 Bd8 $5 (18... Ned7 {black can repeat as he is now threatening
to play d6-d5}) 19. b4 h5 $5 {with the idea of h4-h3} 20. a3 (20. Nb3 d5 $1 21.
exd5 exd5 22. c5 b5 23. Nb6 Bxb6 24. cxb6 Nc4 25. Bxc4 dxc4 $132) 20... h4 $13
21. Bf1 (21. h3 Nh5 $132) 21... h3 22. gxh3 d5 $36) (17. b4 Ne5 18. Qd4 Nc6 {
is a well known trick that forces a repetition if black wants} 19. Qd2 Ne5 20.
Qd4 Nfd7 $5 {of course it is possible to play on}) 17... Ne5 18. b3 h6 $5 {
Taking control of the g5-square is useful. You may not notice now, but this
move is useful, it takes a while until one fully understands how to play the
hedgehog, basically black makes static moves that don't weaken his position,
and he waits for the right moment to strike.} 19. Be3 Ng6 (19... d5 $1 20. cxd5
exd5 21. Nxd5 (21. exd5 b5 $132 {with the idea of Bd6}) 21... Bxd5 22. exd5
Rcd8 {black has plenty of activity for the bishop pair. He is not worse at all}
) 20. Na4 Nd7 21. Qd4 $6 (21. Nxb6 Nxb6 22. Bxb6 Bxe4 23. Bf2 Bb7 {keeps the
balance}) 21... d5 $1 {Korneev does not let his chance slip} 22. Nxb6 {The
best practical chance} (22. cxd5 Bf6 $1 23. Qd2 exd5 24. Nb4 (24. Bxb6 Nxb6 25.
Nxb6 Bg5 $19) (24. Nxb6 Nxb6 25. Bxb6 dxe4 $19) (24. exd5 b5 25. Nb6 Nxb6 26.
Bxb6 Bc3 {white collapses} 27. Qd3 Nf4) 24... b5 25. Nb2 Rcd8 $1 26. Nxd5 Bxd5
27. exd5 Bxb2 $19) 22... e5 23. Nxd7 exd4 24. Nxb8 dxe3 25. cxd5 Rxb8 26. Nxe3
Bg5 $15 27. Rc3 Bxe3 28. Rxe3 f5 29. Bc4 fxe4 30. fxe4 Ne5 31. d6+ Nxc4 32.
bxc4 Rxe4 33. Rxe4 Bxe4 $19 34. Kg1 Kf7 35. Kf2 Bc6 36. Rd2 Ke6 37. Ke3 Rb4 38.
Rd4 Ra4 39. Rg4 Kxd6 40. Kd4 g5 41. h4 Bd7 42. Rg3 g4 43. a3 Be6 44. Rc3 h5 45.
Rc2 Rxa3 46. c5+ Kc6 47. Ke5 Bd5 48. Rd2 Ra2 {0-1 (48) Szuk,B (2416)-Korneev,O
(2623) Hungary 2008 CBM 127 Extra [Castellanos,R]} *

