1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Qc7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. a3 (7. Bd3 {
Black equalizes immediately with} Nc6 8. Nxc6 dxc6 $11) 7... b6 8. Be3 {
White does not have any significant sideline here. The bishop goes to e3, the
pawn to f3 and so on.} Bb7 9. f3 d6 10. Be2 (10. Rc1 {does not change much})
10... Be7 11. O-O Nbd7 (11... O-O {is preferable in my opinion. The reason is
that with the rook on a1, white has the extra option of playing a4. So as a
rule of thumb, wait for white to move his a1 rook before developing the knight.
} 12. a4 {can be met with} Nc6 13. Rc1 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Nd7 $11) 12. Rc1 O-O 13.
b4 {White starts taking space on the queenside. A common approach. Again,
there aren't many worthy alternatives to this move.} (13. Qd2 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Qb8
15. Bf1 {it is a simple transposition if white plays 15.b4} Rfe8 16. Kh1 Bd8 $5
{typical play for black, the idea is to have Bc7 available, so d6-d5 comes in
with greater strength} 17. Bg1 h5 $1 {An idea worth remembering. Whenever
white has played Kh1, this advance could be your source of counterplay. The
plan is simple. Black wants to play h4-h3 sacrificing this pawn but weakening
the white king and the diagonal h1-a8 as well.} 18. Qf2 Ne5 19. b3 Ng6 (19...
h4 {could have been played since} 20. Qxh4 Nxe4 {one of the benefits of
keeping the bishop on d8 and not moving it to c7 so quickly. The bishop keeps
an eye on h4}) 20. b4 h4 21. Nb3 h3 22. g3 Ne5 23. Rd4 Nc6 {1/2-1/2 (25)
Topalov,V (2737)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2652) Tripoli 2004} 24. Rdd1 Ne5 25. Rd4 Nc6 {
1/2-1/2 (25) Topalov,V (2737)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2652) Tripoli 2004}) 13... Rac8
14. Qd2 {White has a few interesting alternatives here:} (14. Nb3 $5 Rfe8 15.
Kh1 Qb8 (15... h5 16. Na4 h4 17. Qe1 h3 18. gxh3 Qb8) 16. Na4 Bc6 $1 {As a
general rule, don't let the knight on a4 stay there for too long as it can
become dangerous} 17. Nd4 Ba8 18. Qd2 h5 $5 {/\ h4-h3} (18... Ne5 $5 19. Rfd1
Nfd7 $13)) (14. Qe1 Rfe8 15. Qf2 Qb8 16. Rfd1 Bd8 $1 {again the standard idea
for black} 17. Nb3 Bc7 (17... d5 $1 {works already} 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Nxd5 (19.
exd5 Bc7 {and black has a dangerous initiative} 20. g3 $2 Rxe3 21. Qxe3 Bxg3 {
beware of this tactic} 22. d6 (22. hxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Kh1 Ng4 {winning}) 22... Bxd6
$19) 19... Nxd5 20. exd5 Qe5 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 22. Rd3 Nf6 {getting back the pawn
with full equality}) 18. g3 h5 $5 19. a4 d5 $1 $36 20. cxd5 exd5 21. Nxd5 Nxd5
22. exd5 Nf6 23. Bg5 Nxd5 24. Bc4 Bd8 25. Bxd5 $2 (25. Bxd8 Rcxd8 26. b5 {
was the only way to keep the balance but I think black is still a tad better})
25... Bxg5 26. f4 Bf6 $17 {Yuneev,A (2428)-Cramling,P (2525) Stockholm 2010})
14... Rfe8 15. Na4 (15. Rfd1 Ne5 $1 (15... Qb8 16. Nb3 {Black can play} Bd8 $5
17. Bf4 Ne5 18. Bxe5 dxe5 {I don't like this structure for black but it seems
we can meet} 19. c5 {with} bxc5 $1 20. Nxc5 Be7 21. N3a4 Qa7 $1 {with the idea
of Bc6 and slowly get off the pressure.}) 16. Na4 Nfd7 {takes us to an
important position for this variation. that we discuss in Ganguly,S (2578)
-Arencibia,W (2535) Torino (ol) 2006} (16... Ned7 $5)) (15. Rc2 Qb8 16. Kh1 (
16. Rb1 Bd8 17. Kh1 h5 {as usual, although black has decent alternatives} (
17... Ne5 18. Na4 (18. Nd1 Nxe4) 18... Nxe4 {is an idea} 19. fxe4 Bxe4 20. Rbc1
Qb7 21. Nf3 Nxf3 22. Bxf3 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Qxf3+ 24. Kg1 b5 25. cxb5 Rxc2 26. Rxc2
Qg4+ $11) 18. Nb3 h4 19. Bf4 Bc7 20. Rd1 d5 $1 {again black takes the
initiative after this move} 21. Bxc7 Qxc7 22. cxd5 exd5 23. Bd3 Qe5 $5 (23...
Qb8 $11) 24. f4 Qh5 25. e5 d4 26. Nxd4 h3 27. exf6 Nxf6 28. Be2 hxg2+ 29. Kg1
Qh3 {Imaginative play from the peruvian Grandmaster and indeed black has
compensation for the piece. White makes a mistake immediately} 30. Re1 $2 (30.
b5 $1 axb5 31. Ncxb5 Rcd8 32. Rc3 Qh4 33. Re3 $16) 30... Rcd8 $19 31. Bf3 Bxf3
32. Rxe8+ Rxe8 33. Nxf3 Qxf3 34. Qf2 Qd3 35. Kxg2 Ng4 {0-1 (35) Valdes Escobar,
A (2387)-Cordova,E (2637) Atlantic City USA 2016}) 16... Bd8 17. Rb1 h5 {
does not change much}) 15... Qb8 16. Rc2 $2 {The problem with the early Na4
move is that white loses control over the break d6-d5 so black should look for
it.} (16. Kh1 h5 {I like this idea} ({Akopian chose} 16... Bf8 17. Rfd1 d5 $1
18. cxd5 exd5 19. Bf4 {Nakar,E (2390)-Akopian,V (2684) St Petersburg 2013} Bd6
$1 (19... Qa7 $5) 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Nf5 Qe6 23. Qg5 g6 24. Nd4
Qd6 25. Nf5 $11) 17. Rfd1 h4 18. Bf1 h3 (18... Bd8 $5) 19. g3 Ne5 $5 20. Nxb6 (
20. Kg1 b5 21. cxb5 axb5 22. Bxb5 Red8 $132 {with d5 coming next black has
enough counterplay for the pawn}) 20... Nxe4 21. Qe2 (21. fxe4 $2 Bxe4+) 21...
Ng5 $1 22. Bxg5 Bxg5 23. Nxc8 Bxc1 24. Rxc1 Rxc8 25. Bxh3 Qa7 26. c5 dxc5 27.
Qxe5 cxd4 28. Rxc8+ Bxc8 29. Bf1 Qb6 30. Bd3 {1/2-1/2 (30) Dominguez Perez,L 
(2678)-Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2555) Havana 2007}) 16... d5 $1 17. cxd5 Rxc2 18.
Qxc2 (18. Nxc2 exd5 19. Bf4 Ne5 $5 $36 (19... Bd6 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Nc3 b5 $1
$11)) 18... exd5 $17 19. b5 (19. exd5 Bd6 {is nearly winning}) 19... axb5 20.
Bxb5 dxe4 {The opening was a disaster for white} 21. Nc6 {this just makes
things worse} Bxc6 22. Qxc6 Bd6 23. Rd1 Bxh2+ 24. Kh1 Rc8 25. Qxc8+ Qxc8 26. f4
h5 27. Bxd7 Nxd7 28. Kxh2 Nf6 {0-1 (28) Fernandez Romero,E (2442)-Korneev,O 
(2601) Elgoibar 2005 [Castellanos,R]} *

