1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3
Bb7 9. f3 Nc6 {GM Walter chooses a different move order} 10. b4 Ne5 11. Rc1 Rc8
12. Na4 d6 13. Be2 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Qd2 Rfe8 16. Rfd1 Nfd7 {Black defends
b6 in order to continue his plan of Qb8-Bd8 etc} 17. Bf1 (17. Nb3 Bc6 (17...
Qb8 {drops b6 and although black gets back the pawn, there is damage on his
queenside.} 18. Nxb6 Nxb6 19. Bxb6 Bxe4 20. Bf2 {black's position is playable
but after} Bc6 21. Na5 Ba4 22. Re1 Bf6 23. Bf1 {white is probably a better})
18. Nb2 Qb8) 17... Qb8 18. Qf2 {Part of white's standard ideas, white can also
begin with the flexible 18.Kh1} (18. Kh1 h5 {by now you should be familiar
with this idea} (18... Bd8 $5) 19. Rc2 h4 20. h3 Bd8 21. Bg1 Nf6 {the knight
goes to h5} 22. Nb3 $2 {A blunder. White understimates black's threats and
misses a tactical shot} Bxe4 $1 23. fxe4 Nxe4 24. Qf4 $2 (24. Qe1 {was the
best defense, however} Ng3+ 25. Kh2 b5 26. Nb2 Bf6 {black is better}) 24...
Ng3+ 25. Kh2 g5 (25... Nh5 $1 26. Qe3 d5 $1 {would have ended the game quickly}
27. g3 Bg5 $1) 26. Qd4 d5 27. Bf2 Nf5 28. Qxe5 Qxe5+ 29. Kg1 {0-1 (29) Oliver
Serrano,A (2094)-Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2562) Calvia 2007}) 18... Bd8 19. Kh1
Ba8 20. Rc2 h5 (20... Ng6 $5) 21. Nb2 h4 22. h3 Bf6 23. Nb3 Ng6 {The opening
phase is over and black has emerged in good shape} 24. Nd3 (24. Rcd2 {it may
look like black is losing the d6 pawn but} d5 $1 25. cxd5 exd5 26. exd5 (26.
Bxa6 Rc3 27. Nd4 dxe4 $132) 26... Rc3 27. Rd3 Rxd3 28. Rxd3 Nf4 $132 {with
plenty of activity}) 24... Bc6 $1 25. Nf4 Ba4 26. Rb1 Nxf4 27. Bxf4 Ne5 28.
Rcc1 {At this point black is already doing very well and now he missed a good
chance of taking the initiative with 28...d5!} b5 $5 (28... d5 {the point is
that after} 29. cxd5 {black has the shot} Nd3 $1 30. Bxd3 Qxf4 31. Rxc8 Rxc8
32. Bxa6 Rc3 33. Nd4 Rc1+ 34. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 35. Bf1 exd5 36. Ne2 Qxa3 37. Qxb6 Qa1
38. Kg1 dxe4 39. fxe4 g6 {black is better}) 29. Na5 d5 30. cxd5 exd5 31. exd5
Rxc1 32. Bxc1 Qd6 33. Qc5 Qd7 34. Bb2 Rc8 35. Qe3 Qxd5 $11 36. Rc1 Rxc1 37.
Qxc1 Kh7 38. f4 Nd7 39. Bxf6 Nxf6 40. Qe1 Kg8 41. Kh2 g5 42. Qe5 Qxe5 43. fxe5
Nd7 44. Nb7 Bb3 45. Be2 Bd5 46. Bg4 Nxe5 47. Nc5 Nc4 48. a4 bxa4 49. Nxa4 Ne3
50. Be2 Nxg2 51. Bxa6 Nf4 52. Bc8 Bc4 53. Nc3 Ne2 54. Ne4 Nd4 55. Bb7 Ne6 56.
Bc8 Kg7 57. Nd6 Bd5 58. Bxe6 Bxe6 59. b5 Bd5 60. b6 Kg6 61. b7 {1/2-1/2 (61)
Ganguly,S (2578)-Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2535) Turin 2006 CBM 113 [Castellanos,
R]} *

