1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bb4 ({Our move order
would be:} 6... Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 d6 10. Qd2 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12.
O-O Nbd7 13. Rfc1) 7. Bd2 Qc7 8. a3 Be7 9. Be3 d6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O b6 12.
Qd2 Bb7 13. f3 Nbd7 14. Rfc1 Rac8 15. a4 $5 a5 {This is a major concession for
black. He voluntarily surrenders the square b5. However, it also has some
advantages. First of all, he blocks the queenside, so there won't be any pawn
storm in the future, second he guarantees the square c5 for a knight which
exerts pressure on white's queenside.} 16. Ndb5 Qb8 17. Bf4 {besides this move
white can also attack d6 immediately with the rook instead} (17. Rd1 {1/2-1/2 
(20) Fernandez Romero, E (2465)-Castellanos, R (2509) Azuqueca Chess Classic
2013} Rc6 $1 18. Nd4 (18. Bf4 Ne5 $13) 18... Rcc8 19. Ndb5 Rc6 20. Nd4 Rcc8 21.
Ndb5 {1/2-1/2 (20) Fernandez Romero,E (2465)-Castellanos,R (2509) Azuqueca
Chess Classic 2013}) 17... Ne5 18. b3 Rfd8 {Black's position is very solid, I
believe there are no great problems here} 19. Kh1 h5 $1 20. Bf1 h4 21. Qf2 Rc5
$1 22. Be3 {it seems now that black will lose material, but in fact, he takes
over the initiative with the thematic blow} d5 $1 23. exd5 exd5 24. cxd5 (24.
Bxc5 Bxc5 25. Qxh4 d4 (25... dxc4 $132) 26. Nd5 Bxd5 27. cxd5 Rxd5 $44) 24...
h3 $1 25. Rd1 $6 (25. Bxc5 Bxc5 26. Qg3 hxg2+ 27. Bxg2 Nd3 28. Rc2 Nxd5 $44)
25... Nxd5 26. Bxc5 Bxc5 27. Qg3 Nxc3 28. Rxd8+ $2 (28. Nxc3 hxg2+ 29. Bxg2 Bd4
30. f4 Bxg2+ 31. Qxg2 Bxc3 32. Rxd8+ Qxd8 33. Rc1 Ng6 34. Rxc3 Qd1+ 35. Qg1
Qd5+ $11) 28... Qxd8 29. Qxe5 (29. Nxc3 Qd4 {wins}) 29... Nd1 30. Ra2 Ne3 31.
Nc3 Nxf1 32. Re2 Nd2 33. Qg3 hxg2+ 34. Rxg2 g6 {A brilliant game 0-1 (34)
Dominguez Perez,L (2726)-Andreikin,D (2687) Capablanca Memorial, Havana 2011} *

