1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Ne7 $5 {I have to say that
this is my second choice here as a Kan player. My main variation has always
been 5...Bc5 followed by 6...Be7 after 6.Nb3. Still, I consider 5...Ne7 to be
equally interesting and considerably less popular nowadays. It has been played
by Carlsen himself and Kramnik too, so it deserves attention. Black's idea is
to continue with Nbc6, sometimes even Nec6 or Ng6 can be played although I
will focus mainly on the idea with Nbc6.} 6. O-O Nbc6 7. Nb3 {It makes sense
for white to retreat his knight to b3 and leave the black knights disturbing
each other, however, black has other plans.} g6 8. c4 Bg7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bg5 {
This is the only serious move to consider here. The alternatives don't put
many problems for black. For example:} (10. Be3 {this allows black to equalize
immediately with} d5 $1 {not only equalize, but white needs to be careful. A
straight liquidation of the center leaves black with a slightly more active
position} (10... f5 $5 {for those willing to fish in troubled waters}) 11. Bc5
(11. cxd5 exd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15) 11... b6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Ba3
(13. exd5 bxc5 14. dxc6 Rb8 $1 {displays the activity of black's pieces}) 13...
Re8 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Be4 Nxc3 16. Qxd8 Ne2+ 17. Kh1 Rxd8 18. Bxc6 Ra7 19. Rad1
Nd4 20. Nxd4 Bxd4 $11) (10. Bf4 {is better than 10.Be3 but we have choices} d5
{again this is perfectly playable} (10... Ne5 {would be my second choice} 11.
Be2 {and now} f5 $1 {with counterplay. The only game in this position
continued with} 12. c5 $6 (12. f3 {is the best move and now black could play}
Qc7 13. Qd2 fxe4 14. fxe4 b6 $13) 12... b5 $1 13. cxb6 fxe4 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxe7
Qxe7 16. Nxe4 d5 17. Nec5 {Panchanathan,M (2525) -Milov,V (2625) Philadelphia
2006 and now} Rb8 {would have been good for black}) 11. exd5 exd5 12. Re1 {
again black is fine} (12. Be2 $6 dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Be2 Qb6 {black is
already slightly better here} 15. Bf3 Be6 16. Qd6 Rad8 17. Qc5 Qxc5 18. Nxc5
Nd4 $15 {Ostrovskiy,A (2351)-Kamsky,G (2744) Rockville 2012}) (12. c5 Ne5 13.
Re1 N7c6 14. Na4 $6 (14. Bf1 Be6 $11) 14... Bg4 15. f3 Bxf3 $1 16. gxf3 Qh4 17.
Bxe5 {Svensson,B (2385)-Grandelius,N (2536) Sweden SWE 2012} Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Nxe5
19. Nb6 Rad8 $15) 12... Be6 $1 (12... dxc4 $5 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Bf1 Nf5 $1 15.
Qf3 Bd7 $1 {very precise move, black can block any pin on the D file by
playing Ncd4} 16. Rad1 Ncd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Qg3 Re8 $11 (18... Nf5 $11)) 13.
c5 Na5 $132) (10. Be2 {is sometimes played. The idea is to control the d5
rupture and keep an eye on d6 as well.} f5 $1 {And now:} 11. exf5 (11. c5 fxe4
(11... a5 $5 {this strange move comes in consideration too}) 12. Nxe4 b6 {
black simply plays for activity} (12... Nf5 {followed by b6 is also possible})
13. Nd6 bxc5 14. Be3 (14. Nxc5 Nf5 15. Nxc8 Qxc8 $132 {this is the typical
position black is hoping for, the piece activity compensates for the bishop
pair and the slightly worse pawn structure.}) 14... Bxb2 15. Rb1 Be5 16. Bxc5
Qc7 17. g3 Nd5 18. Ne4 d6 19. Ba3 {Li,C (2703)-Grandelius,N (2556) Malmo 2012}
a5 $11) (11. f3 f4 12. Bd2 {was played in Sadikhov,U (2134) -Rasulov,V (2537)
Tabriz IRI 2012} (12. g3 g5 13. g4 $6 {this just makes it easy for black to
play on the dark squares} (13. gxf4 gxf4 14. Kh1 Ng6 15. Rg1 d6 $13) 13... b6
14. Bd2 d6 15. Be1 Ng6 16. Bf2 Qc7 17. Rc1 Nce5 18. Nd4 Rb8 19. Na4 {Stisis,Y 
(2380)-Oratovsky,M (2485) Tel Aviv 1996} Bd7 $15) 12... d5 $5 13. cxd5 exd5 14.
exd5 (14. Qc1 d4 15. Na4 g5 $11) 14... Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Rc1 Be6 17. Bc4
Qf5 $11) 11... Nxf5 12. Ne4 {not a great move for white, black has more than
one move to a comfortable position} (12. Bf4 {has been played in a couple of
games, but black has not reacted in the best way. I like the move} b5 $1 13.
cxb5 (13. c5 $2 Bb7 $17 {followed by Ncd4}) 13... axb5 14. Bxb5 (14. Nxb5 Bxb2
15. Rb1 Bg7 $132) 14... Ncd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 $44) 12... Qc7 $5 (12... b6 $5) (
12... a5 $5 13. a4 b6 $15) 13. Ng3 b6 14. Nxf5 Rxf5 15. Rb1 Bb7 $15) 10... h6
11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Ne5 13. Be2 {White has a serious alternative} (13. f4 gxf4
14. Bxf4 N7g6 (14... b5 $5 {is an interesting novelty to mix things up} 15.
cxb5 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 N7g6 17. Bxe5 (17. Bg3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 axb5 {should be fine
for black}) 17... Nxe5 18. a4 axb5 19. Bxb5 Ba6 $44) 15. Be3 {and here the
novelty found by Delchev} b5 $1 $146 16. cxb5 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 axb5 18. Nxb5 Bxb2
19. Bxh6 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 (20. Bxf8 $2 Rxa2 $17) 20... Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Ba6 22. Qc3 e5
23. Nc7 (23. Bxf8 Bxb5 (23... Rxf8 24. Nc7 Bb7 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. exd5 Qb7 27.
Qf3 {Seems better for white}) 24. Bb4 {this is a quite complex position. Black
should be fine, for example} Qf2 $5 (24... Qf6 25. Nd2 Nf4 26. Bc5 Bc6 $11) 25.
Qd2 Qxd2 26. Nxd2 Nf4 27. g3 Nd3 28. Be7 Kg7 $11) 23... Rac8 24. Bxf8 Qxc7 25.
Qxc7 Rxc7 26. Bh6 {and here black can continue in several ways, he has no
problems at all for instance} Bb7 27. Nd2 Kh7 28. Bg5 Rc2 {with counterplay})
13... N7g6 {Play on the dark squares is black's main idea but he has an
interesting alternative here:} (13... f5 $5 14. f3 fxe4 15. fxe4 Rxf1+ 16. Qxf1
b6 17. Rd1 Qc7 18. Qf2 N7g6 19. c5 b5 20. Bh5 Nf4 $1 {eliminating white's dark
squares bishop is worth a pawn} 21. Bxf4 gxf4 22. Qxf4 Bb7 23. Be2 Rf8 $44 {
Grayland,S (2378)-Adams,M (2260) ICCF email 2014}) 14. Qd2 {This is not
dangerous for black} (14. Qd6 $1 {is more challenging} Nf4 15. Bxf4 gxf4 {
and here:} 16. Nd2 (16. c5 Qg5 $1 17. Nd2 (17. Kh1 Nc6 {with idea of Be5 
(Delchev) A possible continuation is} 18. Rg1 {with idea of g3} Be5 19. Qd3 d6
20. g3 fxg3 21. hxg3 Bxc3 22. f4 Qg6 23. bxc3 dxc5 24. Nxc5 b6 25. Na4 Bb7 $132
) 17... Rd8 {with idea of Bf8 (Delchev) I think black is doing OK for example}
18. Rad1 Bf8 19. Qc7 d6 $1 20. Nf3 Nxf3+ 21. Bxf3 Rd7 $1 22. Qb6 Qxc5 23. Na4
Qg5) 16... Qg5 17. Kh1 {We are following the game Caruana,F (2727)-Grandelius,
N (2543) Porto Carras GRE 2011 Here black needs to improve over the game. One
possibility is} b5 $5 {Benko style} (17... Re8 $5) 18. cxb5 axb5 {where black
decent compensation for the material. For example:} 19. Bxb5 (19. Nxb5 f3 $1
20. Nxf3 Nxf3 21. gxf3 Be5 22. Qc5 Qf4 23. Rg1+ Kh7 24. Rg3 Ba6 $15) (19. Nf3
Nxf3 20. gxf3 Qe5 (20... Be5 $5)) 19... Bb7 20. Be2 Ng6 21. a4 (21. Nf3 Qe7 $44
) 21... Bc6 22. Nf3 Qa5 $44) 14... b6 15. f3 (15. a4 {was played in another
recent game but black did very well after} Bb7 16. a5 Rc8 17. Rfd1 Nf4 $5 ({
there was nothing wrong with} 17... Nxc4 18. Bxc4 Rxc4 19. Qxd7 Qxd7 20. Rxd7
Bc8 21. Rc7 Rxc7 22. Bxc7 bxa5 23. Nxa5 Bd7 $15 {black should be better,
slightly}) 18. Bxf4 gxf4 19. Qxf4 Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Rxc4 21. Rd3 (21. axb6 Qxb6 22.
Na5 Rb4 $17) 21... b5 $15 22. Rad1 {Geller,J (2488)-Grachev,B (2628) Moscow
RUS 2016 Here black could have increased his positional advantage by playing}
Qg5 $1 $17) 15... Bb7 16. Bf2 (16. Rac1 Rc8 $11 17. Na4 Bc6 18. Nc3 Bb7) (16.
Rad1 $6 Rc8 {the c4 pawn is weak}) 16... Nf4 $1 $15 17. Na4 $6 Nxe2+ {It is
tempting to take one of the enemy's bishops but black could have seized the
initiative with the thematic rupture b5! here:} (17... b5 18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Rad1
(19. c5 d6 $1 20. cxd6 Bc6 {traps the knight}) 19... d6 20. Nc1 bxc4 21. Nxc4
Nxc4 22. Bxc4 d5 23. exd5 Bxd5 $17) 18. Qxe2 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 b5 20. Qb4 bxa4 21.
Na5 Bc6 22. Nxc6 dxc6 23. Qxa4 Bxb2 24. Rab1 Be5 25. Qxc6 Qd2 $15 {White is
still under a bit of pressure which he can't easily get out from.} 26. Qc5 Bf6
27. Qa3 Rfd8 28. Qa4 Rac8 29. Rbd1 (29. Qxa6 Rc2 {the game goes on}) 29... Qe2
30. Rxd8+ Rxd8 31. Re1 Qb2 32. Qxa6 Rd2 33. Bg3 h5 $19 34. Qc8+ Kg7 35. Qc1
Qd4+ 36. Kh1 h4 37. Bb8 Qf2 {0-1 (37) Jakovenko,D (2759)-Artemiev,V (2671)
Chita RUS 2015 The Week in Chess 1085 [Castellanos,R]} *

