1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Ne7 6. O-O Nbc6 7. Nb3 g6 8.
Nc3 {This is a logical development and probably more dangerous than you might
think. White doesn't waste any time with c4 and plans to exploit the somewhat
weak dark squares immediately through Bg5-Qd2 etc. The theory of this line is
not very developed yet, so I hope to see more of these positions in the future.
There is plenty of room for creativity at the moment.} Bg7 9. Bg5 {The main
move in this position but white has alternatives:} (9. a4 $5 O-O {and now
white has tried:} 10. a5 (10. f4 d5 $1 11. e5 f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qe2 Nf5 14.
Kh1 Qe7 (14... Qd6 $5 $15) 15. Bd2 Bd7 16. Qf2 Nfd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Qg3 {
Florescu,C (2410)-Bologan,V (2585) Romania 1994} Bg7 $15) 10... d5 11. exd5
Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11 {this move is totally fine but also the capture with
the pawn gives black an easy game} (12... exd5 13. Re1 (13. c3 d4 $132) 13...
Be6 14. Nc5 Re8 $1 15. Nxe6 Rxe6 16. Rxe6 fxe6 $11) 13. Be2 Qf5 14. Bd3 Qd5 15.
Be2 Qe5 {black is trying to play for a win} 16. c3 Rd8 17. Qc2 Qc7 (17... Ne7
$5) 18. Be3 (18. Bg5 $5 {is slightly more challenging} Ne7 $1 19. Rfd1 Rxd1+
20. Rxd1 Nd5 21. Qd2 b5 $132) 18... Nb4 19. Qc1 Nd5 20. Bg5 f6 21. Bd2 e5 $15 {
Rydstrom,T (2306)-Blomqvist,E (2531) Uppsala SWE 2016}) (9. Bf4 $5 {is always
interesting} Ne5 {This would be my choice} (9... d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5
(11... Qxd5 12. Qe2 {white should be better}) 12. Re1+ Be6 13. Nc5 O-O 14. c3
$1 (14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bg3 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Qf6 $132) 14... Qe7 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16.
Bg3 {White has two bishops and a better pawn structure. The position is
slightly better for the first player. However, there is plenty of fight ahead.
In the only game, I have with this position black continued with} Rad8 17. Qg4
({Perhaps} 17. Qb3 $5 {gives better chances}) 17... e5 18. f3 Kh8 19. Qh3 Qd7
20. Qxd7 Rxd7 21. Rad1 Bf6 22. Bf2 Kg7 23. h4 Rfd8 24. Bb1 b5 25. g4 e4 $13 {
and black managed to hold: Dunlop,G (2552)-Gefenas,V (2473) ICCF 2015}) 10. Qd2
(10. Be2 f5 11. Bg5 Nf7 12. Be3 fxe4 13. Nxe4 d5 14. Nc3 Nf5 15. Bc5 b6 16. Bb4
Ne5 17. Nd2 $6 Bb7 18. Re1 {was played in Lutz,C (2614) -Bischoff, K (2533)
Essen 2001 Black is doing very well at this point and now} Kf7 {followed by
Re8 and Rc8 would give black a good game}) 10... O-O 11. Be2 (11. Bh6 Bxh6 12.
Qxh6 f5 $132) 11... f5 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Nd5 $5 Nd6 14. Bg5 Ne4 15. Bxd8 Nxd2
16. Nxd2 Rxd8 17. Nb6 Rb8 18. f4 Nc6 (18... Nf7 $5) 19. c3 Bf8 20. Kh1 Bc5 21.
Nxc8 Rbxc8 $11 {Cijs,P (2115)-Luppi,D (2387) ICCF Email 2003}) 9... O-O {
In a recent game I tried the move 9...h6. Without any serious preparation
behind I simply tried to play creative chess, it paid off in the end, but I'm
not sure it is 100% sound. For example:} (9... h6 10. Bh4 (10. Be3 {is also
interesting} d5 11. exd5 exd5 12. Ne2 $5 O-O {Parma,B-Polugaevsky,L Skopje 1968
} (12... Bxb2 {is critical, and after} 13. Ned4 {black should not take the gift
} O-O 14. Rb1 Bc3 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bxh6 Re8) {Draw agreed. The game could
have continued with} 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. c3 Ne5 $13) 10... Ne5 {I'm not sure at
all this is the correct strategy for black, but I wanted a wild game.} ({
I would recommend now the move} 10... d5 11. exd5 exd5 12. Re1 O-O 13. Qd2 Re8
14. Rad1 Nb4 $1 {when black is closer to equality}) (10... b5 $5 {also comes
in consideration} 11. f4 g5 12. Bg3 gxf4 13. Bxf4 Ne5 14. Be3 d6 15. Qh5 N7g6
16. Rad1 Rb8 {with a very complex position. Black has ideas of Nc4 or Bf6-g5.
Of course there is a risk of getting mated on the way}) 11. f4 g5 $1 {of
course I was hoping for this} 12. Bg3 gxf4 13. Bxf4 N7g6 14. Be3 h5 (14... b5 {
would transpose to 10...b5}) 15. Be2 b5 {continuing in my style} (15... Qh4 $1
{was better, black is not worse}) 16. h3 (16. Qd2 $1 $14 {would have made my
game much more difficult}) 16... Qh4 $132 17. Bf2 $2 Qg5 $15 18. Bc5 $4 (18.
Kh1 {was the only way} Ng4 (18... Nf4 19. Bf3) 19. Bg1 Ne3 20. Bxe3 Qxe3 $15)
18... Nf4 $19 19. Rxf4 Qxf4 20. Nd5 exd5 21. Qxd5 Rb8 22. Rf1 Qh6 23. Rf5 d6
24. Bxd6 Bxf5 25. Bxb8 Qe3+ 26. Kh1 Bxe4 {0-1 (26) Meneses Gonzalez,K (2310)
-Castellanos Rodriguez,R (2482) Las Palmas ESP 2017}) 10. Qd2 d6 11. Rad1 ({On
} 11. Bh6 {black could play} e5 $1 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Rad1 Be6 14. Be2 Bxb3 15.
axb3 Nd4 16. f4 f6 17. Bc4 Rc8 $132) 11... Qc7 12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 b5 14. f4
f6 (14... b4 {is an improvement mentioned by Delchev and now after} 15. Ne2 f5
16. Kh1 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Bd7 {with an unclear position. I think black is doing
fine. One plan could be Rf7-Raf8 or simply Rae8 and play in the center with Nf5
}) 15. h4 $6 {This move is a mistake. White should have kept the tension and
most importantly should not put his queen in danger. The rest of the game is
not relevant to our discussion. In conclusion, these lines are yet to be fully
explored, and what I have shown above is just a sample of the type of
positions that can arise from this opening.} (15. Kh1) (15. a3) 15... Rf7 (
15... Nd8 $1 {would have given black better chances} 16. f5 exf5 17. Qf4 (17.
exf5 Bxf5) 17... b4 18. Ne2 Nf7 19. Nbd4 Ne5 20. exf5 Nxd3 21. Rxd3 Bxf5 22.
Nxf5 Nxf5 23. Nd4 Ng7 $15) 16. h5 Rg7 17. Rf3 Bb7 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Qh4 Rf8 20.
Qf2 Rh7 21. Bf1 Kg7 22. g3 b4 23. Ne2 e5 24. Rfd3 Nc8 25. Nc5 Qe7 26. Nxb7 Qxb7
27. Bg2 Rfh8 28. c3 a5 29. Nc1 a4 30. cxb4 Nxb4 31. R3d2 Qd7 32. a3 Nc6 33. b4
axb3 34. Nxb3 exf4 35. gxf4 Rh3 36. Bf3 Rxf3 37. Qxf3 Rh3 38. Nc5 Rxf3 39. Nxd7
Rxf4 40. Rc1 N6e7 41. Re2 {1/2-1/2 (41) Wiwe,A (2197)-Stripunsky,A (2589)
Copenhagen 2007 CBM 119 ext [Castellanos,R]} *

