1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Ne7 6. O-O Nec6 $5 {This move
order leads to different positions than 6...Nbc6. Black no longer plays g6.
Instead, he opts for a more standard development with d6-Be7 and eventually
Nd7 (in case white avoids trading knights)} 7. Be3 {Let's have a look at some
alternatives here:} (7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. Qg4 $5 {is a dangerous option. It is not
clear how to get the pieces out} (8. c4 Bc5 $1 9. Nc3 O-O {followed by d6 and
eventually e5}) (8. f4 Be7 (8... Bc5+ 9. Kh1 O-O 10. c3 d5 11. e5 f5 $5 {
has never been tried}) 9. Nd2 (9. Be3 O-O 10. Kh1 d6 11. Qf3 {Pasiev,R (2384)
-Artemiev,V (2524) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013} (11. c3 b5 $13) 11... Nb4 $1 12. Nc3
Nxd3 13. cxd3 b5 $11) 9... b5 10. a4 Rb8 11. axb5 axb5 12. e5 $6 Nb4 $1 13. Be4
d5 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Kh1 O-O $15 16. c3 Nd3 17. Bxd3 Qxd3 18. Nf3 Qf5 19. Qe2
Bb7 $17 {Safarli,E (2463)-Milov,V (2676) Baku 2007}) (8. Be3 {transposes to
the game}) 8... h5 {seems to be a natural response} 9. Qe2 (9. Qh3 {This move
has scored well in practice since Akopian beat Milov in a rather short game.
However, black could play less suicidal than the swiss Grandmaster and try
something like} d5 $5 (9... h4 $5) 10. exd5 exd5 11. Re1+ Be7 12. Qg3 O-O {
This position needs future tests, but it looks like black is fine. For example}
13. Bf4 (13. Nc3 d4 14. Ne4 h4 15. Qf4 Nb4 $132) 13... Bh4 $1 14. Qe3 Nb4 15.
Nd2 Bf6 16. Be5 Bg5 17. f4 Bh4 18. g3 (18. Rf1 Re8) 18... Bf6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20.
Nf3 Bg4 $132) 9... Ne5 10. Nd2 Be7 $146 11. Rd1 Nxd3 12. cxd3 d6 $11) (7. Nb3 {
is a typical reaction with the idea of leaving the black knight on b8. However,
I don't think it's very useful for white. After black develops the knight
eventually to d7, the knight on b3 is out of play, so it's difficult to say
white has forced a concession on black's development.} d6 {and now:} 8. Nc3 (8.
c4 Nd7 9. Nc3 b6 10. Be3 Be7 11. Be2 (11. f4 O-O 12. Qf3 Nc5 $1 13. Bb1 Bb7 $11
) 11... O-O 12. Rc1 Nc5 (12... Bb7 $5) 13. Nd4 Bb7 {was fine for black in
Kavalek,L (2625)-Vasiukov,E (2560) Manila 1974}) 8... Nd7 9. f4 Be7 10. Qf3 O-O
11. Be3 Qc7 12. Qh3 Nb4 13. Rac1 b5 14. a3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Qd8 16. Nd4 Bb7 17. b4
{½-½ (17) Jansa, V-Vasiukov, E Cienfuegos 1975 I already prefer black's
position here}) ({On} 7. c3 {The Serbian GM Robert Markus has tried} Bc5 8. Be3
d6 9. Nd2 (9. a4 O-O 10. Nd2 Nd7 11. h3 Ba7 12. Qe2 Nf6 ({Here black can try
different moves, for example:} 12... Qc7 $5) ({or} 12... Nde5 $5) ({one idea
that I like is} 12... Nce5 13. Bc2 Nf6 {the plan is to go to g6 with the
knight, play Bd7 and Qc7 and at some point maybe e6-e5}) 13. Rfd1 Qc7 14. Nxc6
bxc6 15. Bxa7 Rxa7 $13 {Rade,M (2434)-Markus,R (2673) Mali Losinj CRO 2017})
9... O-O 10. Qe2 Nd7 11. Rad1 Qc7 12. f4 {This falls into the thematic rupture}
e5 $1 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. f5 b5 15. Kh1 {Firat,B (2460)-Markus,R (2651) Otocec
SLO 2016} Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Qc5 (16... Bb7 17. f6 Nxf6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 19. Qh6 Kh8
20. Qxf6+ Kg8 21. Rf1 d5 22. Qh4 f5 $1 23. Rxf5 Rxf5 24. exf5 e4 $11) 17. Qh3
Bb7 18. g4 f6 $13) 7... Nxd4 8. Bxd4 Nc6 9. Be3 {transposes to the game} Be7 (
9... Qc7 $5) 10. Nd2 (10. c4 $5 {if you search the database you will find
white has done very well with this move. It seems that the right plan for
black is to fight for the center with the move} b6 $1 {with the idea of Bc5
next. Otherwise, black is simply cramped in a hedgehog without much
counterplay.} 11. Nc3 Bc5 12. Qh5 d6 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Kh1 Ne5 15. Be2 Ng6 16.
Rad1 Bb7 17. a3 e5 18. b4 Bd4 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 Qc2 21. Rc1 Qa4 22. Qh3 O-O
{½-½ (21) Hergott, D-Kochyev, A (2540) Graz 1981 Here both sides can find
improvements but I'm confident about 10...b6! and 11...Bc5 idea.}) 10... O-O {
Here Carlsen went for the position with the IQP with the move 10...d5} (10...
d5 11. exd5 exd5 {white should have a small edge here, but of course, black is
still quite solid. Carlsen shows the plan for black, similar as in the French
defense.} 12. Nb3 O-O 13. Re1 Re8 14. c3 Bd6 15. Qc2 g6 16. Bc5 Bc7 17. Rxe8+
Qxe8 18. Qd2 Qe5 19. Qh6 Bf5 20. Bxf5 Qxf5 21. Nd4 Qe4 22. f3 Qe8 23. Nxc6 bxc6
24. Bd4 Be5 {Shirov,A (2755)-Carlsen,M (2733) Morelia/Linares 102/(125) 2008})
11. c3 {It is necessary to prevent Nb4} b5 (11... Qc7 $5 {was Kramnik's choice}
12. Nc4 {is harmless} (12. f4 $1 {is critical, and there are not games with
this move. A sample continuation could be} d6 13. Qe2 b5 14. Rac1 Bb7 15. Nf3
Nb8 $5 $132 {with idea of Nd7}) 12... b5 13. Nb6 Rb8 14. Nxc8 Rfxc8 15. a4 Ne5
16. axb5 axb5 17. Bd4 Nc6 18. Be3 b4 19. Ba6 Rd8 20. Qe2 bxc3 $15 {Black is
already slightly better Leko,P (2751)-Kramnik,V (2759) Nice 2009}) 12. f4 Bb7
13. Nf3 Na5 {Black needs to hurry up and start active play on the queenside so
Artemiev goes for the direct Na5 with the idea of Nc4} (13... b4 $5) 14. b3 {
This prevents black's idea, but it also weakens white's queenside.} (14. Qe2 {
was a possibility here} Qc7 15. Rad1 Rac8 16. Nd2 $5 (16. Kh1 Nc4 17. Bc1 d6 {
black seems fine}) 16... d5 (16... f5 $5) 17. e5 Nc4 18. Nb3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 b4
$132) 14... Qc7 15. Rc1 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 17. Kh1 Qe3 (17... Nc6 {followed by
Ne7 is one idea here, however it is possible that black wanted to keep an eye
on the advance c3-c4} 18. e5 h6 $1 19. c4 Qb4 $5 (19... bxc4 20. Rxc4 Qe7 21.
Bb1 $14) 20. Bb1 Ne7 21. Qxd7 (21. Qd3 g6 22. Qxd7 Bxf3) 21... Bxf3 22. Rxf3
bxc4 $132 {black survives the attack} 23. Qd6 Qxd6 24. exd6 Nc8 $1 25. bxc4
Nxd6 26. c5 Rac8 27. Rff1 $14) 18. Ne5 Nc6 $1 {just in time} 19. Rf3 (19. Nxd7
Rfd8) 19... Qa7 20. Ng4 (20. Nxc6 Bxc6 {just gives black an easy game}) 20...
f5 $1 {This puts an end to white's hope for f4-f5-f6 and at the same time
opens the diagonal for the bishop on b7.} (20... Ne7 {was also possible} 21.
Rg3 f5 22. exf5 exf5 $1 23. Ne3 (23. Ne5 d6 24. Nf3 Rf6 25. c4 Be4 $132) 23...
Rae8 {transposing to the game} (23... Rf7 {with a solid position})) 21. exf5
exf5 22. Ne3 Ne7 23. Rg3 Rae8 $1 $132 {transposing to the game} (23... Rf7 {
with a solid position} 24. Qc2 Qc5 {looks decent for black. He can continue
then with Bc6 or Rc8. Everything is well defended}) 24. b4 $6 (24. c4 $5 Kh8)
24... Qb8 $132 {suddenly black starts creating some threats} 25. Qf1 $6 (25. c4
Qxf4 26. cxb5 axb5 27. Bxb5 Qxb4 28. Bxd7 f4 29. Rb1 Qe4 30. Qb3+ Kh8 31. Qxb7
Qxb7 32. Rxb7 fxe3 33. Kg1 e2 34. Rb1 Rd8 35. Bg4 Nf5 36. Rgb3 {with equality.
Of course, this is all very difficult to find!}) 25... Ng6 $15 26. Nxf5 Be4 {
Here black missed a strong idea:} (26... Kh8 $1 27. Rc2 Nxf4 28. Rf2 g5 $3 $17
{and white is in big trouble with Qe5 coming next}) 27. Bxe4 Rxe4 28. Nd4 Rexf4
29. Rf3 Rxf3 30. Nxf3 Ne5 $15 31. Qd1 Nxf3 32. Qd5+ Kh8 33. gxf3 Qe8 {Of
course black is slightly better, but Giri managed to hold the draw in the end}
34. Rc2 h6 35. Qe4 Qh5 36. Rd2 Rxf3 37. Qa8+ Kh7 38. Qe4+ Rf5 39. Rd5 Qf3+ 40.
Qxf3 Rxf3 41. Rd6 Rxc3 42. Rxa6 Kg8 43. Ra5 Kf7 44. Rxb5 Rc1+ 45. Kg2 Rc2+ 46.
Kg3 Rxa2 47. Rb6 Rd2 48. b5 Rd3+ 49. Kg2 h5 50. Rb8 g5 51. Rd8 Ke6 52. Rg8 Rd2+
53. Kg3 Rd3+ 54. Kg2 Kf5 55. Rf8+ Ke5 56. Rg8 Kf6 57. Rf8+ Ke5 58. Rg8 Kf4 59.
Rf8+ Kg4 60. Rf2 Rd6 61. h3+ Kh4 62. Rb2 Rb6 63. Rb4+ g4 64. hxg4 hxg4 65. Rd4
Rxb5 66. Rxd7 Rb2+ 67. Kg1 Kh3 68. Rd3+ g3 69. Rd1 {1/2-1/2 (69) Giri,A (2785)
-Artemiev,V (2682) Sochi RUS 2017 The Week in Chess 1173 [Castellanos,R]} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13- 5.Nc3 b5"]
[Black "6.g3 - Sidelines for black"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B41"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "68"]
[SourceDate "2017.07.23"]
[SourceVersionDate "2017.07.23"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 (3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 {
would be the usual move order}) 3... a6 4. g3 b5 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4
{Here black's main move is 7...Nf6 which I analyze in Zapata-Bruzon next on
the database. However, I want to give our readers a couple of practical ideas.
Of course, I am not aiming to find a comfortable equality in any of these
lines but to make you aware of some possibilities you can employ to surprise
your opponents. would be the usual move order} Ne7 $5 {This is my
recommendation. A less known line which leads to complicated positions. Before
moving along there is also another move here for black that has been played a
few times by the GM Meijers, that move is 7...h5!?} (7... h5 $5 {it looks like
a joke, but these ideas are common nowadays. There is a very little number of
games played with this move. All I can say is that it's at least worth trying
in blitz and rapid games. Let's see some of the games available so far:} 8. O-O
{this does not interfere with our idea} (8. h3 b4 9. Na4 Nf6 10. Qd3 (10. O-O
Bxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Re1 d5 {without the moves h5/h3 white has here Nxe6
followed by Qh5+ a line mentioned in Zapata-Bruzón. See next game}) 10... d5
$5 ({Here is one trick} 10... h4 11. g4 Qa5 12. b3 Nxe4 $1 13. Bxe4 Qe5 $15)
11. e5 Ne4 12. Be3 (12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. f3 Nc5 14. Qg6+ Kd7 $17) 12... Nd7 13.
Nf3 Bc6 14. b3 Bb5 15. Qd4 Qc7 {white is totally lost Pucher,S (2135)-Meijers,
V (2477) St Chely d'Aubrac 2004}) (8. a3 h4 9. Be3 Nc6 10. f4 Na5 {black
already has good counterplay here with Rc8 and Nc4 coming} 11. Qe2 Nc4 12. Bc1
Rc8 $17 {Piccoli,V (2016)-Meijers,V (2458) Cutro 2009}) (8. h4 {just looks bad
to leave that square weak on g4} Nf6 9. a3 Qc7) 8... h4 9. g4 $6 (9. Re1 $1 {
is strong here of course} Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Be3 {with the idea of Nd5 next.
White is better, but of course, there is a complicated game ahead. For instance
} Rb8 (11... Bb7 12. Nd5 $1) 12. Nd5 d6 13. Ba7 Rb7 14. Bd4 hxg3 (14... Ne7 15.
Ne3 hxg3 16. hxg3 Ng6) 15. hxg3 e5 16. Be3 Bd7 {anticipating Nb4. Black now
wants Ne7 or Nf6} 17. c3 Ne7 $13) 9... h3 $1 10. Bh1 Qc7 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. f3 b4
13. Na4 Nc6 14. Be3 Nge7 15. Rfd1 O-O {was great for black Calandri, F (2130)
-Meijers,V (2514) Assisi 2008}) 8. O-O Nec6 {Of course there is always the
question on which knight should go to c6? Both are possible} (8... Nbc6 9. Nb3
{seems critical and it's the reason why I prefer Nec6} Ng6 10. f4 Be7 ({
Maybe black could try} 10... Na5 $5 {and speed up things on the queenside with
Rc8 etc.}) 11. Be3 O-O 12. h4 Re8 13. h5 Nf8 {Llaneza Vega, M (2468)-Granda
Zuniga,J (2599) Barcelona 2008} 14. h6 g6 15. e5 {looks better for white}) 9.
e5 {The most natural move trying to ''punish'' black's provocative play} (9.
Nb3 d6 10. f4 Be7 {with the typical sicilian position} 11. f5 {I consider this
direct approach to be the only critical thing.} O-O 12. Be3 {and here} exf5 (
12... Bf6 13. fxe6 fxe6 14. Rxf6 $5 (14. e5 Bxe5 15. Qg4 Nd7 $1 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 {
seems to hold as well}) 14... Rxf6 15. e5 Rf7 16. exd6 Nd7 17. Ne4 Nce5 18. Ng5
Bxg2 19. Nxf7 Nxf7 20. Kxg2 Nf6 {and again black is holding fine}) 13. exf5 Nd7
{is not pretty but it is practical} 14. Nd4 Rc8 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17.
Nd5 Nf6 18. c3 Re8 {white is slightly better}) 9... Qc7 10. Re1 $6 {This
natural move already is a slight mistake that allows black an easy game} (10.
Nf3 $1 $146 {is the engine's suggestion} d6 (10... Nxe5 $6 11. Nxe5 Bxg2 12.
Nxf7 Kxf7 13. Kxg2 Qc6+ 14. Kg1 b4 15. Na4 $1 d5 (15... Qxa4 $2 16. Qf3+) 16.
c3 $16) (10... Na5 11. Re1 $16) 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Ne4 Be7 13. Bf4 e5 14. Bg5
O-O 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Qd6 Qxd6 17. Nxd6 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nbc6 19. Rfd1 g6 20. c3
$14) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. Qxd4 Nc6 13. Qg4 (13. Qf4 Be7 14. Be3 (14.
Qg4 O-O-O $1 $132) 14... O-O 15. Ne4 f6 (15... Qc7 $5 16. Bc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Ne7
{when I prefer black's prospects}) 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Nxf6+ Rxf6 18. Qd6 $6 (18.
Qe4 $11) 18... Rf5 $1 19. Bf4 $2 Rd5 20. Qa3 Nd4 $17 {Lopez Silva,H (2386)
-Hellsten,J (2554) Santiago de Chile 2005}) 13... h5 (13... Rc8 $5) 14. Qf3 Rb8
15. Qe4 {It is difficult for white to create anything in this position. Even
for a tactical genius like Sutovsky. White is already worse} Nb4 (15... h4 $5)
16. Re2 Be7 17. a3 $6 (17. Qxb7 Rxb7 18. a4 bxa4 19. Rxa4 O-O) 17... Qxe4 18.
Rxe4 (18. Nxe4 Nc6 19. f4 f5 $1 $15) 18... Nxc2 $17 19. Ra2 b4 20. axb4 Nxb4
21. Ra4 O-O 22. h4 Rfc8 23. Bg5 Bxg5 24. hxg5 Nd3 25. Red4 Nxe5 26. Re4 Rxb2
27. Rxe5 Rxc3 28. Rxa6 Rc1+ 29. Kg2 Rcc2 30. g4 Rxf2+ 31. Kg3 Rg2+ 32. Kh4 Rh2+
33. Kg3 h4+ 34. Kf3 Rhf2+ {CONCLUSION: The move Ne7-Nec6 is interesting
although probably inferior if white plays the strong 10.Nf3 Even in this case,
nothing too bad happens so it may be worth taking the risk. 0-1 (34) Sutovsky,
E (2607)-Svidler,P (2742) Rishon Le Ziyyon 2006 CBM 114 ext [Castellanos,R]} *

