1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O
{This white's main move. The rest don't cause black any problems. Let's see} (
8. Qe2 b4 $5 (8... Qb6 {is tried sometimes. The idea is to kick the knight out
of d4 and then come back to c7} 9. Nb3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. a4 b4 12. a5 (12.
Na2 a5 $15 ({or} 12... d5 13. e5 Ne4 $132)) 12... Qc7 13. Na4 Rc8 14. c3 bxc3
15. Nxc3 Be7 16. Bf4 {½-½ (16) Marjanovic, S (2511)-Hellsten, J (2511)
Kallithea 2003 Black has nothing to worry about here}) 9. Na4 Qa5 10. b3 Nc6
11. Bb2 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 13. Bb6 (13. Be3 Nxe4 14. Nb6 Rd8 15. Nc4 Qb5 16. Bd4
$1 d5 17. Nxe5 Qxe2+ 18. Kxe2 Be7 $11) 13... Qb5 14. Qd3 {The only try for an
advantage} (14. Qxb5 axb5 15. Nc5 Bc6 16. O-O {black can take a draw if he
wants now with} Rb8 17. Ba7 Ra8 $11) 14... Be7 15. O-O Rc8 16. Rac1 O-O 17.
Rfe1 Rfe8 18. Be3 h6 19. Bd2 Bc6 (19... Bf8 $5) 20. Nb2 Qb7 (20... Bc5 $5) 21.
c4 $6 Bc5 $15 {Balashov,Y (2580)-Chuchelov,V (2535) Deutschland 2001}) (8. Qd3
$6 {the queen is exposed here to attacks from c5 or e5 with the knight. This
line is irrelevant and black just develops normally for example:} d6 9. O-O
Nbd7 10. a3 Ne5 (10... Be7 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Re1 O-O 13. f4 Rac8 14. Be3 Rfe8 15.
Rad1 Bf8 16. Nb3 Ba8 17. g4 Qc4 18. Qf3 d5 $132 {Pena Duarte,F (2226)
-Oratovsky,M (2501) Donostia ESP 2017} (18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 f5 {was even
stronger})) 11. Qe2 Rc8 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. f4 Nc4 14. Rd3 Be7 15. b3 Nb6 16. Bb2
O-O 17. h3 Nfd7 18. Rad1 Rfd8 19. Kh2 Nc5 {Gilg,K-Huebner,R Detmold 1967}) (8.
a3 Qc7 9. O-O d6 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. a4 b4 $1 12. Na2 (12. Nd5 exd5 13. exd5+ Ne5
14. c4 {is the best try} (14. f4 O-O-O $132) 14... bxc3 15. f4 Be7 16. fxe5
dxe5 17. Nf5 Bc5+ 18. Be3 cxb2 $15) 12... Nc5 13. Nxb4 (13. f3 {This is just
too pasive} e5 14. Nf5 a5 15. c4 h6 16. b3 g6 17. Ne3 h5 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. cxd5
Ba6 20. Bf1 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 Rc8 $15 {was very easy for black in Simonian,H (2445)
-Korneev,O (2598) Sareyn IRI 2017}) 13... Ncxe4 14. Nd3 (14. c3 Be7 15. Qc2 d5
{looks good for black}) 14... Rc8 15. Re2 (15. c3 Be7 $11) 15... Be7 16. Qe1 d5
17. Bf4 Qb6 $11) (8. Bg5 $2 h6 $1 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. O-O Nc6 11. Nxc6 {and here
both captures give black a good game} Bxc6 $1 {This is my preference here} (
11... dxc6 12. Qe2 e5 13. a4 b4 14. Nb1 a5 (14... Bc5 $5 15. Nd2 a5 16. Rfd1
O-O $11) 15. Qe3 Bd6 16. Nd2 Qe7 17. Nb3 c5 18. Nd2 Ba6 19. Rfd1 c4 20. Bf1 Bc5
$13 {Adams,M (2680) -Short,N (2660) Groningen (m/1) 1997}) 12. Qe2 Qe5 $1 $15
13. f4 $2 {This just makes it easy for black} (13. Rfe1 Rc8 $15) 13... Qc5+ 14.
Rf2 (14. Kh1 b4) 14... b4 15. Nd5 $2 {Lobron,E (2507)-Quesada Perez,L (2402)
Matanzas CUB 2017} (15. Nb1 $17) 15... Bb5 {would have won the game} 16. c4 (
16. Qe1 exd5 17. exd5+ Kd8) 16... bxc3 17. b4 Bxe2 18. bxc5 Bxc5 19. Nxc3 Bh5
$19) 8... b4 {Now we enter in a series of forced lines} 9. Na4 {The most
dangerous move} (9. Nd5 exd5 10. exd5 Bc5 $1 {It is very difficult for white
to prove compensation for the piece here} 11. Re1+ Kf8 12. c4 d6 13. Bf4 Nbd7
14. Nc6 Qb6 15. Qf3 h6 16. Bh3 g5 17. Be3 g4 18. Bxg4 Nxg4 19. Qxg4 Bxc6 20.
dxc6 Ne5 $19 {Rozentalis, E (2618)-Plischki,S (2422) Teplice CZE 2014}) (9. e5
Bxg2 10. Kxg2 bxc3 11. exf6 Qxf6 {followed by Bc5}) 9... Bxe4 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11.
Re1 Nc5 $5 {I think this is the most solid move for black} (11... d5 12. c4 $1
{gives white a strong initiative.} (12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 Qf6 15.
Rxe4 Qxe5 16. Rxe5 Kf7 17. Re3 Nd7 $1 {is the main line. The endgame is
considered balanced and there a bunch of games available})) 12. c3 $5 {The
most dangerous, in my opinion. Let's see the alternatives} (12. Nxc5 Bxc5 13.
Qf3 Ra7 {and now:} 14. Nf5 {black simply plays} (14. Be3 {is met with} Qb6 $1 {
remember this move} 15. Qg4 O-O 16. Rad1 d6 (16... d5 $17) 17. h4 Kh8 18. h5 h6
$17 {Khakimov,T (2228) -Bryzgalin,K (2439) Voronezh 2004}) 14... O-O 15. Nh6+
gxh6 16. Bxh6 f5 {wins}) (12. Qf3 Ra7 13. Be3 (13. Nxc5 {transposes to 12.Nxc5}
) 13... Nxa4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxa7 Nc6 16. Rxe6+ (16. Rad1 Qc8 $17) 16... dxe6
17. Qxc6+ Qd7 $19) (12. c4 Nxa4 13. Qxa4 {and now black can try} Qb6 (13... Bc5
14. Nb3 Be7 15. c5 Nc6 16. Bf4 O-O 17. Rad1 Qc8 (17... a5 $1 $17 18. Nd4 Rc8)
18. Bd6 Bxd6 19. Rxd6 Ra7 20. Na5 {Vallejo Pons,F (2711)-Ghaem Maghami,E (2551)
Almaty KAZ 2016} Rc7 $11) 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Rad1 O-O $15) 12... Nxa4 $1 {Only
move} 13. Qxa4 bxc3 $146 {a risky novelty} (13... Qb6 14. Be3 (14. Qd1 bxc3 15.
bxc3 Nc6 16. Bf4 Be7 17. Rb1 Qc5 18. Rb7 Nxd4 19. Qxd4 Qxd4 20. cxd4 {Despite
the exchange of queens white has compensation for the pawn and black must keep
playing carefully. I would say chances are equal} f6 21. Rc1 g5 22. Bc7 (22.
Be3 Bd6 $1 $15) 22... Rc8 23. Kg2 h5 $13 {Chaika,I (2480)-Lifanov,V (2429)
ICCF 2013}) 14... Bc5 15. Rad1 O-O 16. a3 bxc3 17. b4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Qc6 $17 19.
Qb3 d6 20. Re3 Nd7 21. Rxc3 Qb7 22. Rdc1 $44 {Shchukin,D (2344)-Kalegin,E 
(2471) Voronezh 2011}) 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Rxe6+ Kf7 (15... Be7 $1 16. Bg5 Nc6
17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Rae1 cxb2 19. Rxe7+ Qxe7 20. Rxe7+ Kxe7 21. Qe4+ $11) 16. Re5
Be7 17. Qc4+ $6 (17. Qb3+ Ke8 18. Bg5 Nc6 19. Bxe7 Nxe7 20. Rae1 Rf8 21. Rxe7+
Qxe7 22. Rxe7+ Kxe7 23. Qxc3 $16) 17... Ke8 18. Bg5 Nc6 19. Rxe7+ Nxe7 20. Re1
Rc8 $4 (20... cxb2 21. Qb4 d6 22. Rxe7+ Qxe7 23. Bxe7 Kxe7 24. Qxb2 g6 {
with good draw chances}) 21. Qe2 Kf7 22. Qf3+ Kg6 23. Bxe7 Qa5 24. Qg4+ Kh6 25.
h4 {1-0 (25) Zapata,A (2483)-Bruzon Bautista,L (2689) Bogota 2011 [Castellanos,
R]} *

