1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. Be2 {I believe this move
does not cause black too much trouble. With the white knight already developed
to c3 black obtains good counterplay. It would be an entirely different thing
if white plays Be2 without the knight on c3. See the next game in the database.
} Bb7 7. O-O {The alternative is} (7. Bf3 $5 {and here I like the move} Ne7 $5
{In the style of the previous lines analyzed in the repertoire.} 8. O-O (8. Bg5
h6 9. Bh4 Qb6 {is good for black. For example} 10. a4 Nbc6 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12.
axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. O-O Bc5 15. e5 O-O 16. Bg3 Bd4 17. Qe2 b4 18. Na4
Qa5 19. Bxc6 Bxc6 20. Rd1 Qd5 $1 $19 {Zaitsev,I (2417)-Ghaem Maghami,E (2446)
Moscow 2000}) (8. e5 Nbc6 $1 9. Bf4 Ng6 10. Bg3 Bb4 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O
13. a4 bxa4 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxc6 dxc6 16. Rxa4 Qd5 {black was at least equal
Kalka,A (2389)-Neverov,V (2485) Jerusalem ISR 2015}) 8... Ng6 $1 9. e5 ({
As usual in these lines white can try tricks with Nd5 so} 9. Re1 {comes in
consideration} Nc6 10. a4 b4 11. Nxc6 (11. Nd5 Nce5 $1 $15) 11... Bxc6 12. Nd5
Bc5 13. c3 (13. Be3 $142 Bxe3 14. Nxe3 O-O $11) 13... bxc3 14. Nxc3 O-O {
with the king, safe black can only be better in this position.} 15. Be3 Qa5 16.
Bxc5 Qxc5 17. Rc1 Rab8 $17 {Kalashian,D (2380)-Sjugirov,S (2653) Yerevan ARM
2014}) (9. Be3 {has never been tried} Qc7 $5 10. g3 Ne5 11. Bg2 Be7 $11) 9...
Qc7 (9... Nc6 $5 $146 {sees a solid equalizer} 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Bxc6 dxc6 {
is absolutely nothing for white} 12. f4 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 O-O {
followed by Rfd8}) 10. Bxb7 Qxb7 11. f4 Nc6 $11 12. Nxc6 (12. Be3 {is well met
by} b4 $5 13. Na4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Rc8 15. Rf2 Nh4 $1 {an idea worth remembering,
the knight will go to f5} 16. Qd3 Nf5 17. Rd1 Be7 18. c4 bxc3 19. Bxc3 h5 $1
$11) 12... Qxc6 13. Qe2 Nh4 $1 14. Ne4 Nf5 $11 {This knight is the pride of
black's position and virtually untouchable} 15. c3 h5 16. Bd2 Bc5+ 17. Kh1 h4
18. Rf3 Rc8 19. Be1 d5 20. exd6 Bxd6 21. Nxd6+ Qxd6 {the chances are equal,
but i like black with the super strong knight on f5 Guseinov,G (2609)-Kamsky,G
(2702) Baku (rapid) 2010}) (7. a3 {is possible but it is not a move we should
worry about in the Sicilian. Black can continue with} d6 8. O-O Nf6 {and Nbd7
with a good position}) 7... b4 $1 {Black cannot refuse this offer} 8. Na4 Bxe4
9. Bf3 {again this white's principal approach} (9. c3 Nf6 10. Bg5 Nc6 11. f3
Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc6 13. Nb6 Rb8 14. Nc4 {Kapnisis,S (2366)-Panagopoulos,N (2281)
Athens 2002 and now black should have played} Bb5 {with a clear edge}) (9. Re1
$5 Nf6 10. Bf3 d5 {is similar to the game}) 9... Nf6 10. Bg5 (10. Bxe4 {
seems critical} Nxe4 11. Re1 {and now} (11. Qf3 d5 12. c4 bxc3 13. Nxc3 Qf6 $1
$15) 11... d5 {the safest} (11... Nf6 12. Qf3 Ra7 13. Be3 Rc7 14. Nf5 {looks
scary}) 12. c4 (12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 Qf6 15. Rxe4 Qxe5 16. Rxe5
Kf7 17. Re3 Nd7 $11) 12... bxc3 13. bxc3 Bd6 $1 14. c4 O-O 15. cxd5 Bxh2+ 16.
Kxh2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Qxf2+ $11) 10... d5 $5 {I like this move by Korneev. Black
needs to be careful here} (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 d5 12. Rae1 Be7 {and white can
take on e6 now with anything, and although I think black survives, it is not a
pleasant ride} 13. Rxe6 $36 (13. Nxe6)) 11. Bxe4 (11. Bxf6 gxf6 (11... Bxf3 12.
Nxf3 gxf6 {leads to a wild position where black seems to be holding as well}
13. Nd4 Bd6 14. Qh5 O-O 15. Rad1 f5 {'='} 16. Nb6 Qxb6 17. Qg5+ $11) 12. Qe2 (
12. c4 bxc3 13. bxc3 Nd7 14. Re1 Bg7 $5 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Rxe4 O-O $15) 12...
Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Bd6 14. Qh5 O-O 15. Rad1 (15. Rfd1 Nd7 $1 16. Rd3 Re8 17. Rh3 Nf8
$15) 15... Nd7 (15... f5 $11 16. Nb6) 16. Rd3 Re8 17. Rh3 Nf8 18. f4 f5 19. Qh6
Rc8 20. Rff3 Ng6 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 {with a very unclear game where black's chances
are not worse}) 11... dxe4 12. c3 {white has played very logically so far and
now we can improve on black's game with} Be7 (12... bxc3 13. Nxc3 Be7 {black
is one move away from castling, and there are no signs of attack. Black should
be at least equal here. One possible continuation could be} 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15.
Qc4 O-O 16. Rfd1 Qb7 17. Qe2 Nbd7 18. Nxe4 Rac8 $11 {/=/+}) 13. cxb4 O-O 14.
Re1 $6 {The rest of the game is irrelevant from a theoretical point of view.
White could have kept an edge with the solid 14.a3 keeping a strong structure
on the queenside.} (14. a3 $1 $14) 14... Bxb4 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Rxe4 Rd8 17.
Qf3 Qxf3 18. Nxf3 Bf8 19. Rc1 Nd7 20. Rec4 e5 21. Rc7 f6 22. h3 e4 23. Nd2 Bd6
24. Rxd7 Rxd7 25. Nb6 Bf4 26. Nxd7 Rd8 27. g3 Bxd2 28. Rc7 e3 29. fxe3 Re8 30.
Nc5 Bxe3+ 31. Kf1 a5 32. a3 Bd4 33. b4 Re3 34. b5 Bxc5 35. Rxc5 Rxa3 36. b6 Rb3
37. Rxa5 Rxb6 38. Kg2 Rb2+ 39. Kf3 Rb3+ 40. Kg2 Re3 41. Ra7 Kf8 42. h4 Re7 43.
Ra5 Kf7 44. Kf3 Rd7 45. Rb5 Rd3+ 46. Kf4 Kg6 47. Ra5 Rb3 48. Rc5 Rb4+ 49. Kf3
Rb3+ 50. Kf4 h5 51. Ra5 Kh6 52. Ra6 Rb1 53. Kf3 Rf1+ 54. Kg2 Rf5 55. Ra7 Rb5
56. Kf3 Rb3+ 57. Kg2 Kg6 58. Rc7 Ra3 59. Rb7 Ra6 60. Kf3 Rc6 61. Ra7 Rb6 62.
Rc7 Ra6 63. Rb7 Ra3+ 64. Kg2 Ra2+ 65. Kf3 Ra6 66. Rc7 f5 67. Rc3 Re6 68. Rb3
Re4 69. Rb6+ Kh7 70. Rb5 Kg6 71. Rb6+ Kf7 72. Rb7+ Kf6 73. Rb6+ Re6 74. Rb8 Ra6
75. Rf8+ Ke5 76. Re8+ Re6 77. Rh8 g6 78. Rd8 Rd6 79. Re8+ Kf6 80. Ra8 Rd3+ 81.
Kf4 Rd4+ 82. Kf3 Rg4 83. Ra6+ Ke5 84. Ra5+ Ke6 85. Ra6+ Ke7 86. Rb6 Kf7 87.
Rb7+ Kf6 88. Rb6+ Kg7 89. Rb7+ Kh6 90. Rb6 Re4 91. Ra6 Kg7 92. Ra7+ Kf6 93.
Ra6+ Re6 94. Ra8 Rb6 95. Kf4 Rb4+ 96. Kf3 f4 97. Ra6+ Kf5 98. Ra5+ Kf6 99. Ra6+
