1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 a6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 b5 6. Bd3 {This is by far
white's most popular setup} Bb7 (6... Qb6 {is a very interesting line and will
take it in consideration for future updates of this repertoire.}) 7. O-O (7.
Qe2 Nc6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. O-O {see 9.Qe2}) 7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 {Other moves don't
cause any trouble for black. For example:} (8. Be3 Ne5 (8... Nxd4 $5 9. Bxd4
Ne7 10. f4 Nc6 11. Be3 Be7 $13) (8... Nf6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. e5 b4 11. exf6 bxc3
12. fxg7 Bxg7 13. Qg4 Qf6 14. bxc3 Qxc3 15. Rab1 h5 16. Qb4 f5 $11 {Petrisor,A
(2335)-Fedorov,A (2618) Eforie Nord 2010}) 9. f4 Nxd3 10. cxd3 Nf6 $13 {
I like this type of positions for black. The plan is Rc8-Be7 castle and at
some point try to activate the bishops.}) (8. Nf3 d6 {followed by Nf6 and Be7})
8... Bxc6 9. Re1 {This is white's main move. Of course, the idea is to throw
Nd5 on the next move. Black should play precisely. Let's have a look at the
alternatives:} (9. Qe2 {This is the second most popular move here. Black can
respond in several ways, here is my preference:} Bc5 $5 {is considered the
main move} (9... Nf6 {seems to be a safe option, for now} 10. a3 $5 (10. e5 b4
$1 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {Fell,S (2255)-Flores,D (2595) Villa Martelli ARG 2016
} Qc7 $5 $146 13. Bf4 Be7 14. Rfd1 O-O $11) 10... Qc7 (10... d6 $5 11. a4 $1 {
is white's idea}) 11. Re1 (11. e5 {[#] is critical} Nd5 (11... Ng8 $5 12. Bf4
Ne7 13. Bg3 Qb7 14. f3 (14. Ne4 Nf5 $132) 14... Nd5 15. Ne4 Be7 $13) 12. Bd2
Be7 13. Rfe1 O-O 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qg4 f5 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. c3 Rf7 {black is
pretty solid}) 11... Qe5 $5 (11... d6 $5 12. a4 {is not scary now because of}
b4 13. Na2 d5 14. e5 Ne4 $132) 12. Be3 {Tissir,M (2426)-Chernyshov,K (2556)
Cappelle la Grande 2005 And now black should have continued in creative style
with:} (12. f4 Bc5+ 13. Be3 Bxe3+ 14. Qxe3 Qc7) 12... g5 $1 13. Rf1 h5 14. f4
gxf4 15. Bxf4 Qc5+ 16. Kh1 h4 17. Be3 Qe5 18. Qf2 (18. Bf4 $11) 18... h3 19. g3
Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Bxe4+ 21. Kg1 Bg6 22. Bd4 Qh5 {with wild complications. I can't
say for sure what's happening, but with a human eye the position looks double
edged.}) (9... Qb8 {seems reliable to me, let's see:} 10. Bd2 (10. a4 b4 11.
Nd5 Bd6 12. f4 {[#] Vert agressive but black has a good answer.} (12. h3 Ne7
$146 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. Bxa6 Qe5 15. Bd3 Rxa4 $11) 12... f5 $1 {this makes
white's center shake} 13. e5 Bxd5 14. exd6 Nh6 (14... Kf7 $1 {and Qxd6 leads
to a slightly better position for black}) 15. c4 bxc3 16. bxc3 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 O-O
18. c4 Bc6 19. Be3 Qb4 20. c5 Ng4 $11 {Baramidze,D (2569)-Markus,R (2586)
Heraklio 2007}) (10. Kh1 Be7 $5 11. a3 d6 12. f4 Nf6 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Rae1 Qb7
15. e5 Nd7 $1 {no need to open lines} 16. Qg4 (16. exd6 Bxd6 17. Ne4 Be7 18. f5
exf5 19. Rxf5 g6 $11) 16... g6 17. b4 {Zelcic,R (2521)-Horvath,C (2546) Rabac
2004} Qc7 $132) 10... Bd6 11. f4 {Komiagina,M (2263)-Stukopin,A (2458) St
Petersburg 2010} b4 (11... Ne7 $5 12. e5 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Nf5 $13) 12. Nd5 f5 {
is a nice counter} 13. e5 Bxd5 14. exd6 Kf7 15. c4 bxc3 16. Bxc3 Nf6 $11) 10.
a4 b4 11. Nd5 a5 $1 {I think this the only move to keep the balance.} (11...
Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxa6 (13. a5 Bd4 {with idea of Qc5!}) 13... Bxe4 {
I think the position is kind of dull for black after either of the options
white has now:} 14. Bb5 $5 {this is unpleasant} (14. Qxe4 Rxa6 15. Qb7 Ra5 16.
c4 O-O 17. b3 d5 $1 $146 (17... f5 18. Rd1 $14) 18. Qxe7 Bxe7 19. cxd5 Bf6 $1
20. Ra2 (20. Rb1 Rxd5) 20... Rxd5 21. Be3 Rfd8 {white is slightly better, but
black should be able to hold}) 14... Bd5 15. c4 bxc3 16. bxc3 O-O 17. a5 Rac8
18. Be3 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Rc5 20. Rfb1 Rfc8 {Szczepanski,Z (2498)-Figlio,G (2438)
FICGS email 2011 Although I think black is solid, the position is passive.})
12. Bf4 (12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Ne7 {I see no great problems for black. The
position resembles the game Cheparinov-Kamsky Gibraltar 2014}) 12... d6 $1 13.
Rfd1 (13. Be3 Ne7 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Ne3 O-O 16. b3 Qc7 $11) 13... Ne7 14. Nxe7
Qxe7 15. Bb5 Rc8 16. Qd3 e5 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 O-O 19. c4 bxc3 20. bxc3 Qc7
$11 {Efroimski,M (2268)-Vertetics,A (2425) Zalakaros HUN 2016}) (9. Bf4 b4 $1 {
since white cannot play Nd5 black should go ahead with this move} 10. Ne2 (10.
Nb1 Nf6 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Re1 O-O {is harmless for black} 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bg3 f5
$1 15. exf6 Nxf6) 10... Nf6 11. c3 $5 $146 Bxe4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13. cxb4 Be7 14.
Qd4 Nf6 15. Rfd1 O-O 16. Be5 Rc8 17. a3 Rc6 $5 $11 (17... d5)) (9. e5 f5 {
is the typical response.} 10. a4 (10. exf6 Nxf6 11. Qe2 Bd6 $132) 10... b4 11.
Nb1 (11. Ne2 Bc5 12. Nf4 {and now black can play} Nh6 $1 {the knight is great
on h6, in the future it can go to f7 and support the advance of g5} 13. Nh5 $6
{fails to} Ng4 $1 14. Nxg7+ Kf8 {and black is already better for instance} 15.
Bxf5 (15. Nxf5 Rg8 {white is in trouble}) 15... exf5 16. Nxf5 Rg8 $19) 11...
Ne7 12. Nd2 Ng6 13. Nc4 Bc5 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. Nd6+ $6 Ke7 16. fxe3 Nxe5 $17 17.
Bxf5 $2 Qb8 $19 18. Qh5 Kxd6 19. Rad1+ Kc7 20. Bxe6 Kb7 {black is a piece up
and went on to win. Filippov,A (2589)-Horvath,C (2537) Bol 2014}) 9... Bc5 {
This is one of black's most solid options. The idea is to develop the knight
to e7 and finally complete the development. Besides this move we should also
know that 9...Qb8 is a good alternative} (9... Qb8 10. a4 (10. Qe2 Bd6 $1 11.
e5 Bc7 12. f4 f5 13. Be3 Ne7 14. a3 O-O 15. Qf2 {[#]} g5 $1 {Thematic move in
this structure. This gives black a powerful initiative} 16. Qg3 Rf7 $1 17. h4 {
and now} Rg7 $3 {would have given black a much better position after} (17... g4
$2 {Edouard,R (2688)-Dearing,E (2418) England 2013}) 18. hxg5 h6 $1 $17 {
a great example of counterplay in this line}) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Bd6 12. Qh5 (12.
h3 Ne7 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qe2 {Nevednichy,V (2547)-Kamsky,G (2667)
Cappelle la Grande FRA 2016} O-O $11) (12. Qg4 $5 {can be dangerous for black}
Bxh2+ 13. Kh1 Kf8 14. Nf4 h5 $5 (14... Bxf4 15. Bxf4 e5 16. Be3 Nf6 17. Qh4 h6
18. f3 Kg8 19. b3 a5 20. Rad1 $44 {1/2 (25)-1/2 0-1 (25) Pasqua,G (1618)
-Galvin,J (1828) LSS email 2012}) 15. Qg5 Bxf4 16. Bxf4 d6 17. e5 h4 $132 {
with interesting play. For example:} 18. exd6 h3 19. f3 Qa7 20. Be3 Qd7 21. Bc5
Nf6 $11 22. Qg3 Nh5 23. Qg5 Nf6 $11) 12... Ne7 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. b3 {and now} (
14. e5 a5 {black can't castle for a while but he doesn't need to. He can play
h6-Qb7-Rc8 in order to create some counterplay.} 15. Qg4 Kf8 $1 $13) 14... O-O
$1 {Kamsky improves over his own game against Nakamura where he played 14...a5
and lost pretty badly} 15. Bb2 (15. e5 g6 16. Qh6 f5 $1 $11) 15... f6 16. Re3
Rf7 17. Rf1 g6 (17... a5 $5 $11 {is probably a better idea}) 18. Qe2 Bd6 (18...
Bc5 $5 19. Rf3 Bd6 20. Bxf6 Bf4 $1 21. Bb2 Bxh2+ 22. Kh1 Rxf3 23. Qxf3 Be5 $13)
19. e5 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 fxe5 21. Rxe5 $14 {Kulaots,K (2556)-Kamsky,G (2661)
Stockholm SWE 2017}) 10. Qh5 {white has some important alternatives here} (10.
a4 b4 11. Nd5 Ne7 {and now} 12. Be3 (12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Be3 a5 14. e5 Bxe3 15.
Rxe3 Qg5 16. Be4 Rc8 17. Bxc6 Rxc6 18. c3 bxc3 19. bxc3 Qd8 $1 20. Rb1 Qc7 21.
Rb5 O-O 22. Qb3 Rc5 23. h3 h6 24. Rxc5 Qxc5 25. Qb5 Qxb5 26. axb5 Rc8 27. Rd3
Rc5 $11 {was equal in: Guseinov,G (2623)-Pantsulaia,L (2612) Konya TUR 2016 I
don't see where white can improve in this line so 12.Nxe7 doesn't seem
promising for me.}) (12. Bg5 $2 {is insufficient} exd5 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. Re5
Qc7 ({even} 14... f6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Rxd5 Nxd5 17. Qh5+ Kf8 18. Qxd5 d6 $19)
15. Rxd5 Nxd5 16. Qf3 Qe5 17. Bc4 Qxg5 18. Bxd5 Rc8 19. Re1+ Kd8 20. Bb7 Re8
21. Rd1 Qd2 22. Kf1 Qxc2 23. Bxa6 Rc6 {0-1 (23) Nikolenko,O (2533)-Vorobiov,E 
(2606) Ulan Ude 2009}) 12... Bxe3 13. Nxe3 a5 14. Qh5 Ng6 (14... O-O 15. e5 Ng6
) 15. b3 (15. e5 Qh4 16. Qxh4 Nxh4 17. Bb5 Rc8 18. Red1 Ke7 19. b3 Ng6 20. Nc4
Bd5 21. Rd4 Bxc4 $5 22. Rxd7+ Kf8 23. bxc4 Nxe5 24. Ra7 g6 25. Rxa5 Nxc4 26.
Ra7 Na3 {the endgame is even Sprenger,J (2510)-Balogh,C (2647) Netherlands NED
2015}) 15... O-O 16. e5 Qe7 $5 {Black wants to transfer the queen to c5 where
it will be more active and also with support some ideas with f5 since the e5
pawn might be pinned.} 17. Ng4 (17. Rad1 Qc5 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Qg4 Rf7 20. Qd4
Qe7 $1 {in such positions it's important to keep the queens on the board to
generate counterplay against the white king.}) 17... Qc5 (17... Bxg2 {it's
hard to say if both players missed this move} 18. Re3 d5 $1 19. exd6 Qxd6 20.
Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qe5 Qxe5 22. Rxe5 Bf3 $17) 18. Qh3 {and now Kamsky played} f5 {
which might be a little dubious. Cheparinov, I (2672)-Kamsky, G (2709) Caleta
ENG 2014} (18... d6 {seems like a good freedom move here and I think black is
totally fine.})) (10. Be3 {is a major move I think. Black continues with} Bxe3
11. Rxe3 Ne7 12. e5 $1 (12. Qh5 Ng6 (12... O-O $5 $146 13. e5 (13. Rh3 h6 14.
Rg3 Qc7 $1 {looking at Qxg3} 15. Re1 f5 $132) 13... g6 14. Qh6 f5 $11) 13. Ne2
d6 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Nf5 exf5 16. exf5+ Ne5 17. f4 Qb6 18. Rae1 Kf8 19. fxe5 dxe5
20. f6 gxf6 21. Kh1 h6 22. Qh4 Rc8 23. Rf3 Rc6 24. a4 Rd6 {1/2-1/2 (24)
Malisauskas,V (2483)-Nisipeanu,L (2664) Novi Sad 2009}) 12... Ng6 (12... d5 $5
{is wild} 13. Ne2 (13. exd6 Qxd6 {should not worry black at all}) 13... d4 14.
Rg3 Qd5 15. Rg5 g6 16. Qd2 (16. Nf4 Qc5 $13) 16... h6 17. Nf4 Qc5 18. Rg4 Qxe5
19. Re1 Qd6 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Rxd4 Nd5 22. Bxg6+ Kd8 23. Rde4 Bd7 $13) 13. Ne4
$1 {this critical move has only been tried once. Black reacted by capturing on
e4 and suffering for the rest of the game.} (13. Qg4 Qh4 14. Qg3 Ke7 15. a3
Qxg3 16. hxg3 f6 17. f4 fxe5 18. fxe5 Rhc8 {Tiviakov,S (2670)-Balogh,C (2620)
Sibenik 2009 was fine for black}) {I think black should play} 13... O-O $1 14.
Qh5 (14. Rh3 h6 15. Nf6+ gxf6 16. Qh5 f5 17. Qxh6 Re8 $11) 14... Qh4 15. Qxh4
Nxh4 {with even chances}) (10. Qg4 Nf6 11. Qg5 (11. Qxg7 $4 Rg8 12. Qh6 Bxf2+ {
would be nice if our opponents fell for this}) 11... d6 $11) (10. e5 f5 {again}
11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qh3 h5 (12... Ne7 {would be the human way to play it, one
sample line could be} 13. Bh6 Qb6 14. Re2 O-O-O 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bf6 g5 $1 17.
Bxh8 Rxh8 {I believe black has very good compensation for the exchange with
Ng6 coming next}) 13. Be3 Qb6 14. Qh4 Nh6 $5 {looks very provocative but it
seems to work just fine} 15. h3 (15. Qf6 Rg8 $1 16. Bxh6 Be7 {is the trick})
15... Nf7 16. Qf6 Kf8 $5 {this leads to complications very difficult to
evaluate.} (16... Bxe3 17. Rxe3 Rh6 18. Qg7 Qc5 {with the idea of Qf8 and
black is equalizing}) 17. a4 b4 18. a5 Qa7 19. Nd1 h4 20. Bg5 Rh5 21. Bd2 Rh7
22. Bg5 Re8 23. Qxg6 Rg7 24. Bh6 Nxh6 25. Qxh6 Qa8 26. Kf1 Bxg2+ 27. Ke2 Qf3+
28. Kd2 Be7 29. Re3 Qa8 30. f4 Kg8 31. Qh5 Rc8 32. Nf2 Bc5 33. Rae1 Qd5 {
0-1 (33) Tiemann,H (2430)-Lifanov,V (2393) ICCF email 2012}) 10... Qb6 11. Be3
Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Ne7 {The play is very similar to the lines shown above} 13. Nd5 {
This again} (13. Rae1 Ng6 14. e5 $2 {A blunder} Nf4 15. Qg5 Nxg2 16. Ne4 Bxe4 (
16... Nxe1 17. Nd6+ Kf8 18. Rxe1 Qd4 $19 {would have been the simplest}) 17.
Bxe4 Nxe3 18. Rxe3 Rc8 19. Qxg7 Rf8 20. Bxh7 Rc4 $19 {Muzychuk,A (2552)
-Cramling,P (2495) Sochi RUS 2015}) (13. e5 {is the only serious alternative
and I think black should continue now with} Ng6 ({Do not play} 13... Nd5 $2 14.
Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qg5 g6 16. Qh6 {is better for white as seen in Mamedov,R (2689)
-Fedorov,A (2598) Minsk BLR 2017}) 14. Ne4 (14. Ne2 b4 15. Rd1 a5 $13) 14...
Bxe4 15. Rxe4 Rc8 16. g3 (16. a4 bxa4 17. Rexa4 Qxb2) 16... O-O 17. Qe2 Rfd8 {
when I think black can only be slightly worse if anything at all}) 13... Qd8 $1
14. Nxe7 (14. c3 Bxd5 (14... Ng6 15. Nb4 Bb7 16. Bc2 O-O 17. Rd1 Qc7 18. e5
Rad8 $13) 15. exd5 g6 16. Qe5 O-O 17. dxe6 dxe6 {looks about even}) 14... Qxe7
{Black has some problems to complete his development, and his king can be
under attack sometimes but on the other hand, he has a solid pawn structure,
and in most endgames, he is slightly better due to white's vulnerable
queenside. The position should be considered of dynamic equilibrium where both
sides have their chances.} 15. e5 h6 16. Rg3 g6 17. Qe2 Qc5 (17... h5 $5) 18.
a3 $6 {This move gives black an unnecessary break point on b4} (18. Re1 {
at once is better when black can continue with} h5 19. h3 a5 $13) 18... a5 19.
Re1 b4 20. axb4 axb4 21. Qd2 h5 22. h4 Qd4 23. Qg5 Qxb2 24. Qf6 Rg8 25. Be4 (
25. Kh2 Ra1 26. Rxa1 Qxa1 27. Qf4 Qa5 28. Be2 {threatening Bxh5 and Rb3} Rf8
29. Rb3 f6 30. exf6 Qf5 31. Qxf5 exf5 32. Rxb4 Rxf6 $11) 25... Ra1 26. Rge3
Bxe4 27. Rxe4 d5 $15 28. R4e2 Qc3 29. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 30. Kh2 Qd1 31. Qf3 Kf8 (31...
Qd4 $17) 32. Qe3 Kg7 33. Rd2 Qc1 34. Qf4 Rb8 35. g4 hxg4 36. h5 Rh8 37. Qf6+
Kg8 38. Qd8+ Kg7 39. Qf6+ Kg8 40. Qd8+ Kg7 41. Qf6+ {1/2:1/2 Delgado Ramirez,N
(2602)-Kamsky,G (2706) Tromso NOR 2014 The Week in Chess 1031 [Castellanos,R]
CONCLUSION: The Kamsky line b5-Bb7-Nc6 leads to interesting positions, where
black has plenty of resources. It's a solid choice against white's most
aggressive setup.} *

